<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Seeking Major U.S. Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Romania is seeking large
investments from big American companies in a bid to enter the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
A series of U.S. projects in Romania on machine building, the
power industry, road construction through forests, and agriculture
are being discussed, a memorandum aimed at boosting
U.S. investments said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum, composed by the Romanian Foreign Ministry, is
paving the way for an official summer trip by Romanian President
Emil Constantinescu to Washington. The two countries formed a
strategic partnership last year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the development in bilateral cooperation, Romania,
which is eager to gain NATO membership, is still dissatisfied with
the current U.S. capital inflow.
</P>
<P>
The reluctance of major American firms to make substantial
investments leads to negative opinions on the business climate in
Romania, and implicitly on the country's image," said the document.
</P>
<P>
American investments in Romania of 280-290 million U.S. dollars
are not enough to encourage Washington's backing, compared to the
6.2 billion in Hungary, 4 billion in Poland and 1.53 billion in
the Czech Republic, three nations ready to be admitted into NATO.
</P>
</TEXT>
