<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wang Luna Shines in Women's 200m Freestyle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAODING, North China, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Wang Luna became the
most glittering star on the sixth day of the Chinese national
swimming championships as she stunned world champion and record
holder Chen Yan of Liaoning Province here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old Wang failed to show any edge over Chen before
the last 25 meters, shaking off the world champion with a storming
finish in 2:00.70.
</P>
<P>
Chen took the silver in 2:01.52 while Tan Caini came third in
2:03.07.
</P>
<P>
"Her results was just what I had expected before the
competition," Wang's coach Xu Huiqin said. "Her personal best
1:57.32 was ranked second in the world last year, only behind
Chen's 1:57.30."
</P>
<P>
But Xu said that he had not expected Wang could win the title.
"I had thought Chen was too strong for her to beat. But the win
means she has regained form after two months' recovery training."
</P>
<P>
The women's 200m breasttroke was won by Qi Hui in 2:30.86,
followed by Mi Tong in 2:32.51 and Wang Wei in 2:32.61.
</P>
<P>
In the men's competition, Wang Wei from Shanghai led all the
way to touch the pad first in 2:00.56, only 0.31 second outside of
his personal best.
</P>
<P>
Fu Yong, winner of the event in last year's National Games,
settled for the second in 2:03.26 while Shu Xin placed third in
2:04.04.
</P>
<P>
Huang Xin captured the gold of the men's 100m butterfly in
55.05, ahead of Zhang Xiao in 55.17 and Pan Licong in
55.30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
