<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of England to Transfer Banking Supervision to FSA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of England will transfer
its responsibility for banking supervision to the Financial
Services Authority (FSA), which will come into force on 1 June.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference on the Banking Act Report Wednesday,
Michael Food, executive director of the bank, said, "This is the
last such report produced by the Bank of England."
</P>
<P>
On May 6, 1997, the British government announced a major reform
of financial regulation, the transfer of responsibility for
banking supervision from the bank to a single statutory regulator
for all financial services business in Britain.
</P>
<P>
In announcing this decision, Chancellor Goldon Brown emphasized
the aim of delivering more effective and efficient supervision of
financial business, giving firms and customers better value for
money.
</P>
<P>
After the transfer, the bank and the FSA will maintain close
working relationship, as set out in the Memorandum of
Understanding between the Treasury, the FSA and the bank on the
common objective of financial stability.
</P>
<P>
The FSA's future regulatory approach will be to maintain the
standards of banking supervision currently practiced by the bank
and it will continue to implement changes designed to improve the
effectiveness of supervision.
</P>
<P>
The FSA has indicated that its approach to the supervision of
complex groups is likely to evolve and that it will pilot
multi-disciplinary supervisory teams with a limited number of
groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
