<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meeting Ends with Calls to Empower Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The three-day international
conference on gender and good governance ended in Harare
Wednesday with resolutions passed calling to empower women in the
volatile world environment which is dominated by men.
</P>
<P>
The conference was attended by about 100 women politicians and
parliamentarians from Africa, Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
The delegates recommended that there should be a mechanism to
ensure women were treated with equality at government level.
</P>
<P>
They also called upon world governments to ensure an
environment free from the threats of nuclear wars and mass
destructions.
</P>
<P>
They said the environment should be free of local conflicts
which were being used as arenas for weapon testing.
</P>
<P>
The delegates called for increased allocations for the social
sector and severe cuts in defense spending.
</P>
<P>
In international organizations, it was recommended that
multilateral financial institutions must consider debt
cancellations to free resources for human development in
afflicted countries.
</P>
<P>
Steps had to be taken to ensure that the international
political economy was transparent and accountable in the true
spirit of world democracy.
</P>
<P>
The delegates also proposed that women as a group in countries
torn apart by war should be extended stronger support in their
efforts toward conflict resolution, peace making and peace
keeping.
</P>
<P>
The women emphasized the need to have access to media and
communication technologies to facilitate their effective
participation in the governance process.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was organized by the women development division of
the Netherlands Ministry of Foreign Affairs in collaboration with
the Royal Netherlands Embassy in Harare.
</P>
<P>
Its objective was to develop a common understanding of the
role of women in good governance and democratic processes, and to
enhance women's participation in political decision making.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
