<HEADLINE> Muslim League Calls for Dialogs in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The Muslim World League called
on Indonesia's political parties on Wednesday to hold dialogs for
national unity, Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the league Abdullah Saleh Al-Obeid issued
a statement in Mecca, Saudi Arabia, that a constructive dialog
will be the best way to maintain the unity and stability of
Indonesia, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Islamic peoples and organizations are concerned over the
security and stability in the country, Al-Obeid said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he warned against any interference in the internal
affairs of the Muslim country in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Anti-government demonstrations and turmoils took place in
Indonesian capital Jakarta and other cities over the past week,
leading to more than 500 deaths. Demonstrators called for
resignation of President Suharto.
</P>
<P>
Suharto announced in a nationally televised address on Tuesday
that a general election will be held as soon as possible, which he
said he will not stand for. But he stopped short of setting a date
for the vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
