<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Play China in Semi-finals at Thomas Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Defending champions Indonesia and
four-time winners China will meet in a semi-final show-down on
Friday after the final-day group competitions at the 20th Thomas
Cup Badminton Finals here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the other semi-finals set for Friday, runners-up Denmark
will take on Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
China had failed to reach the finals since their fourth victory
in 1990 in Tokyo, finishing as semi-finalists for the last three
championships.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia beat Malaysia and the two finished 1-2 in Group B on
Wednesday. Both sides booked semi-finals berths.
</P>
<P>
South Korea finished third after beating the Netherlands 3-2.
</P>
<P>
China, seeking for the first final since 1990, lost to Denmark
2-3 late Wednesday and took the second place of Group A. Denmark
won the top place of the group.
</P>
<P>
World number one Peter Gade-Christensen gave Sweden a flying
start with his 15-3, 17-16 narrow win over second-ranked Chinese
Sun Jun in the first singles, which was his second win over the
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Having beaten Gade-Christensen twice, Sun, at 22 to win this
year's All-England Open, lost to the Dane in their latest meeting
in the final of this year's Swedish Open in March.
</P>
<P>
Gade-Christensen displayed what he later described as his best
ever performance in the 52-minute thriller, especially during the
first game, which he won 15-3.
</P>
<P>
With volleys and smashes, the Dane kept his pressure on Sun in
the second game. Sun led 2-0 after the match went into setting of
three points following a 14-14 tie in the second game. But the
aggressive Gade-Christensen took the game and the match by winning
three points in a row to make it 17-16.
</P>
<P>
"I'm happy to win this crucial match. Both of us are now in a
very good shape since we did not have any major competitions since
the Swedish Open," a joyful Christensen said after the victory.
</P>
<P>
"It's like a dream come true," he said. "I'll have no big
problem if we went into a third game. But I'd prefer to win it
2-0," he admitted.
</P>
<P>
Denmark's fourth-ranked Poul-Erik Hoyer-Larsen, 32, showed his
depth of strength when he won the first game 15-6 over China's
world number three Luo Yigang in the second singles. But Luo, at
21 as the semi-finalist at this year's All-England Open, won two
consecutive games 17-16 and 15-10 to win the match and brought
China to a 2-1 lead on the team score. It was Luo's first ever
win over the veteran Dane.
</P>
<P>
After Chinese Duet Zhang Jun and Zhang Wei failed to hold on
after a 14-14 tie and lost the decisive third game and the second
doubles 1-2, the Chinese team's fate hanged on its world number
five Dong Jiong, who had to beat Denmark's Kenneth Jonanssen,
ranked 12th in the world. The two split the two previous
meetings.
</P>
<P>
Jonansson won over Dong 15-6, 2-15, 15-8 for a narrow Danish
victory over China.
</P>
<P>
In the other Group A match Wednesday evening, Sweden won over
hosts Hong Kong, China, 4-1 to take the third place of the group.
</P>
<P>
In Uber Cup's semi-finals on Thursday, defending champions
Indonesia will play Denmark while runners-up China take on South
Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
