<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buyoya, Factions Leaders Agree to All-party Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 20 (Xinhua) - Burundi President Pierre
Buyoya and all the conflicting factions leaders agreed here
Wednesday to attend the all-party peace talks scheduled on June
15 in Arusha in northern Tanzania for a national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Mwalimu Julius Nyerere, the international facilitator of the
Burundi conflict, made the statement following his two-hour
meeting at his residence in the Msaasani suburb of Dar es Salaam
with visiting Major Buyoya.
</P>
<P>
"Buyoya and all the other leaders have agreed to take part in
the Arusha meeting," Nyerere told a press conference at his
residence. "They don't set any preconditions for attending the
meeting."
</P>
<P>
Buyoya, who arrived here this morning for talks with Nyerere,
a former Tanzanian president, also held talks with Tanzanian
President Benjamin Mkapa at the State House at noon before
leaving for Burundi capital Bujumbura Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
A senior aid to Nyerere said the meeting between Nyerere and
Buyoya, the first of its kind held in Tanzania, was "friendly and
constructive."
</P>
<P>
Nyerere has since last Saturday been consulting with various
Burundi leaders in Dar es Salaam in preparation for the all-party
negotiations in Arusha in an effort to reach a national
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The leaders include the Speaker of the National Assembly
Leonce Ngendakumana, former Presidents Jean-Baptiste Bagaza and
Sylvester Ntibantunganya, Chairman of the Front pour la
Democratie au Burundi (FRODEBU) Jean Minani, and Chairman of the
National Council for Defense and Democracy (CNDD) Leonard
Nyangoma as well as a joint government and parliament delegation
led by the Minister for Reconciliation Ambrose Niyonsaba.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere discussed separately with these Burundi leaders at his
residence or at the downtown Sheraton Hotel all the proposals to
prepare for the Arusha negotiations, a secretary of Nyerere's
said.
</P>
<P>
The last regional peace talks held in Arusha last August were
boycotted by Major Buyoya who cited the security concerns and
accused Nyerere of bias against Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Secretary General of the United Nations
Kofi Annan, during his eight-nation African tour, met and
encouraged Burundi President Pierre Buyoya to accept the
mediation by Nyerere over the Burundi crisis to achieve a
national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Annan reaffirmed the U.N. support for the efforts by the
leaders in the Great Lakes region to try to find a way out for
the Burundi crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary General noted that some progress has been made
for Burundi to meet certain conditions set by the regional
leaders for lifting the economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Burundi peace talks were stalled last year after the
Burundi government said it had no faith in Nyerere because he is
both the international mediator in the Burundi political conflict
and an advocate of imposing economic sanctions on the central
African nation.
</P>
<P>
East and central African nations, backed by the Organization
of African Unity (OAU), have imposed economic sanctions on
Burundi since August of 1996, just a few days after Major Buyoya
toppled a civilian government led by President Ntibantunganya.
</P>
<P>
More than 150,000 people, mostly civilians, have died in
bloody conflicts between the ethnic Hutu majority and the ruling
Tutsi minority since the assassination of Melchior Ndadaye, the
first president elected under a multiparty system in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Arms Inspectors Continue Activities Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 20 (Xinhua) -- U.N. arms inspectors continued
their monitoring and inspection activities in Iraq on Wednesday,
with full cooperation from the Iraqi side, the Iraqi News Agency
INA reported.
</P>
<P>
Eleven monitoring groups of the U.N. Special Commission on
disarmament in Iraq, known as the UNSCOM, made surprise and
scheduled visits to 15 sites off monitoring, INA quoted an
official source at the Iraqi National Monitoring Department as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The source said one of these monitoring groups used
helicopters to reach its destination.
</P>
<P>
A biological team made a surprise visit to two sites under
monitoring in Baghdad, while two others were visiting some sites
under monitoring in Neniveh and Qadisiya provinces by helicopters,
said the source.
</P>
<P>
Another biological team returned from Basrah province after it
had finished its activities in several sites there, the report
added.
</P>
<P>
A team responsible for surveying areas of war heads
destruction started its activities on Wednesday and will continue
for 30 days with the aim of counting the remnants of destroyed war
heads in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. inspectors must verify that Iraq is free of weapons
of mass destruction before the U.N. sanctions imposed on the
country in 1990 for its invasion of Kuwait can be lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
