<HEADLINE> Major Mews Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Hard-line military leaders clamped down on the capital of
Indonesia in an effort to choke off plans for a huge demonstration
hours after President Suharto rejected calls to step down, saying
instead that he would hold elections some time in the future.
Barricades also isolated the Parliament building, where thousands
of protesting students had camped overnight.
</P>
<P>
-- Iran trumpeted a Clinton Administration decision to waive
sanctions against three foreign companies that are doing business
there as a moral victory for the European Union and one that
should signal an end to American attempts to deter similar
investments. A government communique called on the United States
to repeal altogether the legislation that requires sanctions on
companies that deal with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- A panel of business leaders, academics and members of
Congress has proposed a rescue of the ailing Social Security
system using a combination of personal investment accounts and
increased retirement age. The group said Tuesday that the plan
would ensure the system's solvency for 70 years without a tax
increase.
</P>
<P>
-- India's May 11 announcement that it had tested nuclear
weapons ignited a frantic effort by the Clinton administration to
dissuade Pakistan from doing the same, beginning with a phone call
from President Clinton to Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
and an 18-hour flight to Islamabad in a windowless military plane,
refueled in the air, by a high-level U.S. delegation.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Pager services were disrupted when a communications
satellite operated by Pan-AmSat spun out of control. PageNet, one
of several firms that use the spacecraft, said more than 80
percent of all U.S. pager users lost service, and that rerouting
may take a day. The satellite also carries advance feeds to
television stations. 
</P>
