<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-20 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU: No Plan to Boycott Israeli Goods From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has no
immediate plan to implement a controversial proposal on excluding
goods produced in Israeli settlements from EU tariff breaks, EU
ambassadors said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with Israeli Finance Minister Yaacov Neeman
Wednesday afternoon, ambassadors of the 15 EU member states
said that the recommendation, proposed by the EU Commission last
week, was "being examined by EU institutions."
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the meeting, Neeman said it was clear that the
EU would not implement the proposed sanctions on settlements'
products. He added that the Israeli government and the EU would
continue the discussions in the near future to solve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
In its report to EU ministers, the EU Commission criticized
Israel's practice of exporting goods produced in Jewish
settlements in the Palestinian territories of West Bank, Gaza
Strip and East Jerusalem, as well as the Golan Heights which was
seized from Syria in 1967.
</P>
<P>
Israel exported these goods to Europe with a "made in Israel"
label, entitling them to enter Europe duty-free in the framework
of EU-Israeli free trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
The commission suggested that since these occupied territories
are not part of Israel, goods produced in Jewish settlements in
these areas should be restricted and excluded from benefits of
the EU-Israeli trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation has infuriated Israeli officials, who
dismissed it as an attempt to prejudge Israel's borders before
these have been duly determined through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu warned Tuesday that the
proposed boycott would "put an end" to any EU role in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
For its part, however, the EU scorned Israel for its
"political motivated reading" of the document. In a statement
issued Tuesday, the EU said that the "restriction" suggested to
be placed over goods produced in Jewish settlements "does not
refer to either sanctions or to a boycott."
</P>
<P>
Israel has been at odds with the EU in the past months over
the EU's attempt to expand its role in mediating the Israeli-Arab
peace process.
</P>
<P>
To match its status as the leading aid provider to the
Palestinian National Authority, the EU has tried in vain to break
the monopoly by the United States on the mediation of the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks. Balancing Washington's
pro-Israeli bias, the EU has been pressuring Israel to end the
settlement activities and make concessions to break the year-long
deadlock in the process.
</P>
<P>
But Israel, blaming the EU for being pro-Arab, has so far
rejected to increase the EU's say in the process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
