<HEADLINE> Out-of-Control Satellite Knocks Pagers Across U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Service to millions of pager
users across the United States was interrupted on Tuesday
afternoon due to a communications satellite out of control.
</P>
<P>
The satellite is Galaxy 4 operated by PanAmSat. It started having
problems about 3:30 p.m. Behind-the-scenes television transmissions
also were disrupted.
</P>
<P>
One of the paging companies estimated that 80 percent to 90
percent of the 40 million to 45 million U.S. pager users lost
service. It would take a day for the company to switch service to
another satellite.
</P>
<P>
Many pager users still don't know why their pagers were not
working.
</P>
<P>
Galaxy 4 was launched in June 1993 aboard an Ariane rocket,
primarily covering the United States, Puerto Rico and the
Caribbean. Los Angeles-based Hughes Communications Inc. is the
major owner of PanAmSat. The satellite is expected to end service
by 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
