<HEADLINE> Annan Condemns Armed Attack Against U.N. Personnel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Wednesday strongly condemned Tuesday's armed attack against
the United Nations personnel in Angola.
</P>
<P>
On May 19, a vehicle patrol composed of a military observer, a
police officer from the United Nations Observer Mission in Angola
(MONUA), an Angolan National Police (ANP) liaison officer, a local
ANP commander, as well as a local interpreter, was ambushed about
five kilometers north of Calandula, Mallange province. The injured
ANP commander escaped from the site of the incident.
</P>
<P>
The MONUA immediately launched a rescue operation. The MONUA
military observer was found Wednesday, very seriously injured, and
evacuated to Luanda. After a long search, the MONUA police officer
was also found and evacuated to Luanda, where his physical
condition is being ascertained. However, the body of the local
interpreter was discovered near the burnt vehicle.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief reiterated in strong terms that the safety and
security of all United Nations personnel in Angola should be
unequivocally respected.
</P>
<P>
Annan also expressed concern over the recent deterioration of
the military and security situation in Angola. He appealed to the
parties, and in particular to the National Union for Total
Independence of Angola, to complete without delay the various
pending tasks under the Lusaka Protocol, in accordance with the
plan submitted to the parties by his special representative for
Angola on May 15, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
