<HEADLINE> Israeli PM Confirms Demand for Aid From U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu Wednesday confirmed reports that he has demanded one
billion U.S. dollars from the United States to help Israeli troop
pullback from the West Bank, Israel Television reported.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the confirmation after a weekly cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Haaretz newspaper has reported that Netanyahu told U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright during their meeting in
Washington last week that when an agreement on the Israeli
withdrawal is reached, Israel will ask the U.S. to give a special
aid of one billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said the aid would be used for security arrangements
in the West Bank, mainly building bypass roads for Jewish
settlements.
</P>
<P>
However, the newspaper quoted U.S. sources as saying that
Albright has not made a response.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that if the U.S. decides to meet Netanyahu's
demand, assistance would also be given to the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The PNA has reportedly asked the U.S. for 100 million dollars
to help fund steps it will be required to take in connection with
Israel's redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the PNA and Israel has been stuck over
the Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank. The U.S. has reportedly
called on Israel to hand over another 13 percent of the West Bank
to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has accepted the initiative. But the Jewish state has
argued that the withdrawal scope in the American initiative will
endanger its security and said it will relinquish no more than 9
percent of the West Bank. 
</P>
