<HEADLINE> Renamo Urges EU not to Back Mozambique's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican National Resistance
Movement (Renamo), the biggest opposition party in the country,
asked the European Union (EU) Wednesday to change its position of
supporting the local elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued here Wednesday, Renamo said the
elections scheduled to be held on June 30, is a "farce", and that
the EU should change its position toward the elections.
</P>
<P>
Renamo also urged the international community and all walks of
life in the country to press the ruling Mozambican Liberation
Front (Frelimo) and its chairman Joaquim Chissano to "respect
truth."
</P>
<P>
Renamo and 15 other opposition parties, had decided to boycott
the local elections on the pretext that Frelimo practised
irregularities during last year's registration for the elections.
They demanded vote re-registration and the participation of the
opposition parties in the management of the electoral
secretariat, but was rejected by the government.
</P>
<P>
The EU, while admitting that there were mistakes in last
year's registration, which it saw only amounted to four percent
in the whole process, said there is no need for another
registration, as the mistakes have been corrected.
</P>
<P>
Reaffirming its position of boycotting the elections, Renamo
said in the communique that "we wish all those who take part,
directly or indirectly, in the elections, must be aware that by
supporting the elections, they are pushing the country to
instability."
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican president and his ruling Frelimo party,
meanwhile, have expressed their stance on many occasions that the
elections would be held as planned even if Frelimo turned out to
be the only party for it in the end.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, the local elections would be held in 33
towns and cities in the country.
</P>
<P>
The EU has not toed the line of the U.S. which has announced
suspension of its financial aid for the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abacha Refuses to Be Parties' Only Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Head of State, General
Sani Abacha may have decided to refuse the invitation by the
country's five political parties to have him as their consensus
candidate for the August 1 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Media reports Wednesday quoted government sources as saying
that he will choose to contest on the platform of the United
Nigeria Congress Party, which has emerged the overwhelming winner
in the local government council, state assembly as well as the
national assembly elections.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, General Abacha may have directed the other
four parties to nominate new candidates.
</P>
<P>
The move, reports said, is to restore the credibility of
General Abacha's transition to civil rule program, by which he
pledged in 1995 to hand over power to an elected civilian
government this October.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, Nigeria's five registered parties all
adopted Abacha as their presidential candidate, a move that drew
strong criticism from both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
A proof of the new development in the transition program arose
last week, when the Congress for National Consensus announced
that it will withdraw its nomination if Abacha fails to respond
to the issue by coming Saturday.
</P>
<P>
General Sani Abacha has been silent on the issue of his
candidacy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
