<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-20 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tunisian President: Israeli Hard-line Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Tunisian President Zine Al-Abidine
Ben Ali Wednesday expressed deep concern over the stalemated
Mideast peace process as a result of the Israeli hardline policy,
saying it gravely threatens the regional stability.
</P>
<P>
Ali made the remarks following his talks here with visiting
Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar on bilateral ties and
regional and international issues of common concern, the Tunisian
presidential spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Tunis Africa Press quoted the presidential spokesman as
saying that the two leaders stressed the necessity of continued
efforts, specially by the peace process sponsors, the U.S. and
Russia, as well as the European Union for reactivating the process
and pressuring Israel to abide by the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also stressed that Tunisia and Spain would play
more effective role in reviving peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Aznar expressed hope that his talks with Tunisian government
officials would help exploring all chances for further improving
the already strong ties between Tunisia and the EU within the
partnership agreement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish prime minister arrived here Tuesday for a two-day
visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
