<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turner's Fund for U.N. Projects Starts Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The 1 billion U.S. dollar
fund set up by prominent U.S. businessman Ted Turner started to
move ahead Wednesday with the first batch of 22 million dollars to
be channeled to women, children and environmental projects.
</P>
<P>
Turner, co-chairman of Times Warner Inc., announced last fall
that 1 billion dollars would be contributed to support the United
Nations in achieving its goals. The money arrives in 10 years with
each year averaging 100 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the main objectives of the United Nations Fund
(UNF), Fund President Timothy Wirth told reporters here Wednesday
that the fund is to support U.N. causes and reforms, to make
Americans better understand the U.N. and to find more contributing
resources for the world body.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the 22 million dollars will go to women and
population programs (9.3 million dollars) in Latin America,
Asia-Pacific and Africa, with another 6.5 million dollars
earmarked for children's health, and 1.4 million dollars for
environmental schemes.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the money goes to such items as food aid, the fight
against drug abuse, poverty alleviation and mine clearance.
</P>
<P>
Turner's gesture was well received by the U.N. which is in a
financial crisis due to debt owed by the United States and other
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
