<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Scientists Find Sporting Gene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- British scientists said Wednesday
that they have found the gene responsible for elite sporting
performance in humans.
</P>
<P>
The fitness gene, a polymorphism of the angiotensin converting
enzyme (ACE), was evident among high altitude moutaineers and a
group of raw army recruits who successfully completed a grueling
10 week physical training program.
</P>
<P>
The study, completed by the Center for Cardiovascular Genetics
at University College London, is thought to have major
implications for the treatment of strokes and cardio-vascular
disease.
</P>
<P>
The researchers identified two varieties of the ACE gene in
human, the I and D class, which are paired in three possible
associations, namely the II, ID and DD.
</P>
<P>
"We have demonstrated that version I alleles are associated
with better endurance performance than the D allele," Dr Hugh
Montgomery, who led the research team, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
DNA samples were taken from a group of 33 high altitude
mountaineers who had all climbed above 7,000 meters without the
use of breathing equipment.
</P>
<P>
These climbers were found to be more likely to carry one of the
I alleles in its two possible forms. Further studies of 15
climbers with ascents of over 8,000 meters without oxygen revealed
that none was of a DD genotype.
</P>
<P>
A second study of 78 army recruits found that those with II and
ID genotype showed improvements in repetitive weight lifting 11
times greater than those with the DD genotype.
</P>
<P>
Scientists believed that the ACE gene may influence physical
performance by increasing the take up of nutrients and oxygen to
muscle cells.
</P>
<P>
"The real benefit of this work is in saving lives. If this gene
does work by making cells more efficient it might be able to stop
cell death when fuel supply is reduced," said Dr Montgomery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
