<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Rightwing Claims 35-Hour Work Week Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- France's rightwing opposition Rally
for the Republic (RPR) and Union for French Democracy (UDF)
Wednesday declared as "unconstitutional" the 35-hour work week law
definitely adopted Tuesday by the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 140 parliament deputies from the RPR and UDF have seized
the country's Constitutional Council to decide whether the law
conflicts with the Constitution or not.
</P>
<P>
The deputies, including RPR and UDF parliament group presidents
Jean-Louis Debre and Francois Bayrou, said that five motives of
the Socialist-drafted law are unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
The law lacks clarity, violates the rules of laws on social
security financing, blocks the constitutionally guaranteed freedom
of taking action and violates the rights of both employers and
employees, they said.
</P>
<P>
The opposition also blamed the law for breaking the principle
of equality, and failing to respect the principle of holding
collective negotiation between social partners coming into law.
</P>
<P>
The law, which was on the agenda of legislative campaign by the
Socialists last year, expects to reduce weekly working time to 35
hours by 2000 in big enterprises and by 2002 in small enterprises
in France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
