<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Gets 6.5 Mln Dlrs From U.N. Foundation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) said Wednesday that it would move quickly
to begin using the 6.5 million U.S. dollars granted by the U.N
Foundation, totaling 1 billion dollars contributed by U.S.
businessman Ted Turner.
</P>
<P>
The 6.5 million dollar grant is part of the first batch of 22
million dollars announced Wednesday to be channeled into women and
population and environmental projects.
</P>
<P>
Turner's money comes in 10 years with each year averaging 100
million dollars in Time Warner stock.
</P>
<P>
Six UNICEF proposals have been approved for immediate work in
Africa, Indonesia and Vietnam on issues ranging from fighting
diseases to demobilizing child soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The largest portion of 2.8 million dollars is for a three-year
guinea worm eradication project in Africa, a goal set eight years
ago at the World Summit for Children.
</P>
<P>
The disease, the result of a parasite found in drinking water,
causes joint deformities, ulcers, fever and debilitating pain.
</P>
<P>
With its partners, the UNICEF will focus on disease control at
the village and district level and on improvements in water
supply.
</P>
<P>
A grant of 1 million dollars will support a battle in Nigeria,
Africa's most populous nation, to fight child killers of measles
and vitamin A deficiency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
