<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Gratis Personnel Should Not Be Accepted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Gratis personnel should not
be used to perform functions that could be carried out by other
United Nations staff members; nor should they be accepted because
of recruitment failure.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made at the Fifth Committee (Administrative
and Budgetary) Wednesday as it discussed use of such personnel and
aspects of the support account for peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
Gratis personnel are staff loaned to the United Nations, free
of charge, by its member states. The General Assembly adopted a
resolution on September 15, 1997 which prescribes the
circumstances under which such personnel may be utilized.
</P>
<P>
They may be accepted for a limited period of time, after a
budget is approved, to provide expertise not available within the
organization. Also, they can be used to provide temporary and
urgent assistance for a new or expanding mandates, pending the
assembly's decision on funds for those mandates.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the committee, Prayono Atiyanto of Indonesia,
speaking on behalf of the Group of 77 developing countries and
China, said members of the Secretariat should be appointed and
should serve according to the relevant articles of the United
Nations Charter.
</P>
<P>
He said that in 1997, the General Assembly had decided to end
the extraordinary practice of using gratis personnel, and in that
regard, the group looked forward to full implementation of the
assembly's resolution.
</P>
<P>
Those gratis personnel that fell beyond the scope of the
provisions contained in the resolution should be phased out
expeditiously, he said, adding that all the functions performed by
gratis personnel should be performed by United Nations staff.
</P>
<P>
The delegate stressed that it was the lack of adequate staff
resources that led to the use of gratis personnel, rather than the
need for specialized expertise not obtainable through recruitment.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's delegate Nester Odaga-Jalomayo said Uganda is
concerned by the acceptance of gratis personnel.
</P>
<P>
He said there was already, in the organization, a growing
tendency to undermine the provision of the assembly's resolution,
which stated that such personnel would be accepted only because
their expertise was otherwise unavailable.
</P>
<P>
He said such personnel should not be brought in to perform
functions that could be served by other staff members. Uganda is
afraid that such personnel would be accepted in order to make up
for recruitment failure.
</P>
<P>
The delegate said Uganda had long been emphasizing the need to
eliminate gratis personnel. Among other reasons, such personnel
had loyalty to their governments and could ultimately be withdrawn
by them at any time, he added.
</P>
<P>
Euy Taek Kim, the representative from the Republic of Korea,
said acceptance of gratis personnel inevitably entailed additional
financial costs for the organization, and the acceptance of gratis
personnel was often the result of insufficient staff resources,
rather than the lack of specialized functions in the Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
He urged the full compliance of the assembly's resolution on
the acceptance of such loaned staff. He welcomed the U.N.
secretary-general's revised guidelines on it and looked forward to
their implementation throughout the United Nations system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
