<HEADLINE> Uganda Releases 42 Sudanese POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- A total of 42 Sudanese prisoners
of war captured by the Ugandan army in March 1997 were released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The hand-over ceremony, held at the Entebbe International
Airport, was presided over by the Chief of Staff of Uganda
People's Defense Forces (UPDF) Brigadier James Kazini.
</P>
<P>
Al-Haji Ali, Assistant Secretary-General of the Sudanese
National Islamic Front, represented the Sudanese government at
the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Radio Uganda said there still remains 72 Sudanese prisoners of
war in Uganda and today's handover was not an exchange but a
gesture of good will from the Ugandan side.
</P>
<P>
Two UPDF soldiers are still in custody in Sudan, it reported.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has put no conditions on the release of these Sudanese
soldiers but just a gesture of political tolerance. It wants to
show that it is for a peaceful solution for the long-standing
conflict between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
However, the report added, Uganda still demands the Sudanese
government to release the abducted children and Abike Secondary
School girls and the two Ugandan soldiers in custody before the
normalization of bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
