<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Hails Waiver of U.S. Sanction on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei on Wednesday hailed the waiver of the U.S. sanction
law on Iran, saying that the U.S. defeat showed Iran's real
strength.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei told the country's Friday prayers leaders that the
U.S. had incessantly attempted to plot against Iran since the
early times of the history of the Islamic revolution with all its
might through its political, cultural and financial means,
according to the Iranian official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
He said that Washington has madly tried to threaten those
countries to withdraw from their economic contracts signed with
Iran, however, all its attempts had met deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
In order to save face from further ignominy, the U.S. recently
retreated from the failed application of d'Amato
extra-territorial law at the international level, he said,
"doesn't this really show the real power enjoyed by the sovereign
state of the Islamic Republic of Iran?"
</P>
<P>
Under strong pressures from the European Union and its members,
U.S. President Bill Clinton announced on Monday to waive the law
and not to punish French, Russian and Malaysian companies, which
have reached a 2-billion-dollar deal with Iran in the field of gas
and oil.
</P>
<P>
Under the D'Amato Act signed by Clinton in 1996, the U.S. would
punish any companies which invest over 40 million U.S. dollars in
the energy sector in Iran. The ceiling was lowered to 20 million
dollars last August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
