<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni, Moi Stress Economic Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
and his Kenyan counterpart Daniel arap Moi Wednesday stressed the
importance of economic integration of the east African region as
an avenue for enhancing development and attracting investors.
</P>
<P>
They made this statement at a luncheon hosted in Moi's honor
by the Uganda Manufacturers Association on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said that the sustainability of all businesses is
based on markets and that the east African market of 100 million
people is good for the manufacturers and is certainly a strong
force in attracting foreign investors to the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that Uganda's contribution in the context of east
African development lies in the area of energy products since
Uganda is richly endowed with water resources.
</P>
<P>
Moi, who is on his three-day official visit to Uganda,
stressed that Uganda's rapid economic growth is essential to the
economic revival in his country.
</P>
<P>
Uganda, Kenya and Tanzania should not be taken as separate
economies but as a unified economic unit, said the Kenyan
president.
</P>
<P>
He called on the business community in the region to strive
for higher quality of their products in order to get more market
shares.
</P>
<P>
The visiting president also pressed for the removal of trade
barriers hindering the economic activities between the members of
the east African cooperation and appealed for concerted efforts
to create conditions favorable for the eventual establishment of
an African common market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
