<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delayed Sale of Copper Mines Likely to Hurt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Further delay in the sale of the
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) is likely to have serious
financial complications on the country's economy, Finance
Minister Edith Nawakwi said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nawakwi said that the government has no financial capacity to
sustain the ailing conglomerate and further delay in privatizing
the mines will derail the current economic program.
</P>
<P>
However, she said that her country will not sell Nkana and
Nchanga mines under duress despite the urgent need to dispose of
the assets.
</P>
<P>
She told a news briefing that even the donor community has
supported Zambia's stand by recommending that the mines should be
sold at a value that is most beneficial to the Zambian people.
</P>
<P>
Part of the reasons for the breakdown of the negotiations
between the Kafue Consortium and the government was that the
bidders refused to take over the 75 million U.S. Dollars of ZCCM
debt as part of the package in the sale of the two biggest mines
of the copper-producing country, according the minister.
</P>
<P>
Nawakwi said a number of industries depending on ZCCM for
sustenance like Chilanga Cement Corporation, Kafireond
Explosives, are likely to lose business if ZCCM collapses.
</P>
<P>
Due to disagreement over the prices of the two mines, Zambia
discontinued the negotiations last month with Kafue Consortium.
The two mines make up 65 percent of the ZCCM assets.
</P>
<P>
Because of copper price falls and outdated equipment, lack of
investment and mismanagement, annual copper output of the country
has decreased gradually to about 300,000 tons in recent years
from its peak 750,000 tons in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
To attract foreign investment, advanced technology and
management to revive the stagnating copper production, the
government has invited foreign tenders for the ZCCM mines and
assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-20 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Warns Against Recognition of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides
Wednesday evening warned against any idea supporting any form
of recognition of the self-styled Turkish Cypriot regime in
northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the 23rd Cyprus International Fair,
Clerides stressed that any such suggestions would be rejected by
the Greek Cypriot side and would harm relations between the
Cyprus Republic and anyone nurturing such ideas.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes "the international community and those
foreign states working toward the resumption of negotiations and
a solution to the Cyprus problem should insist that the
so-called 'Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus' will not be
recognized and that the basis for holding talks will not change."
</P>
<P>
"I would like to stress emphatically that any thoughts of
granting some form of status or recognition to the de facto
situation created and maintained through the continuing illegal
occupation of part of the Cyprus Republic will on the one hand be
unanimously rejected by the Greek Cypriot side and on the other
will harm Cyprus' relations with anyone considering supporting
such ideas," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Clerides' remarks came in the wake of a deadlock in the Cyprus
peace process since last summer when Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash walked out of the U.N.-led peace talks with Clerides in
protest against European Union's decision to start accession
talks with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has said he would not return to the negotiating table
unless his entity in northern Cyprus controlled by the turkish
Cypriots is recognized and the Cypriot government suspends talks
with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the Cypriot government "fervently desires a
solution to be found by peaceful means as soon as possible," that
is why it submitted a proposal for demilitarization in 1993.
</P>
<P>
"This proposal is still valid," he said, calling on all who
are interested in drastically reducing tension in Cyprus to "take
immediate action so the demilitarization proposal is
implemented."
</P>
<P>
Clerides described the present situation as "not only unjust
and absurd, but fraught with dangers for peace and stability in
our region."
</P>
<P>
But he believed that "with the proper preliminary work the
coming months can give other opportunities to achieve the goal of
resuming negotiations."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed coup by Greek Cypriot supporters of union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The international community has been making efforts to help
Cyprus reunify under the bizonal and bicommunal formula sponsored
by the U.N., but so far, no tangible results have been achieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
