<HEADLINE> U.S. Remains Leading Exporter to Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. expanded its market in
Cyprus and remained the number one exporter to Cyprus in 1997 for
the third consecutive year, U.S. Ambassador to Cyprus Kenneth
Brill said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held at the U.S. pavilion in the
23rd Cyprus International Fair, which opened here Wednesday, Brill
said "our share of Cyprus' total imports, including imports for
re-export, grew from 17.8 percent in 1996 to an all-time high of
19.0 percent in 1997."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is participating in the Cyprus Fair as the largest
single-country pavilion. Some 500 exhibitors representing some
1,600 companies from 40 countries are participating the fair.
</P>
<P>
He said trade and economic relations between the two countries
have grown even closer over the years.
</P>
<P>
"As Cyprus is gearing up to join the European Union (EU), it
will face new challenges and opportunities. Our sincere wish is
that EU accession ultimately benefits all Cypriots," Brill added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "as Cyprus moves to liberalize its economy and
respond to growing economic competition globally, Cypriots will
find the U.S. government and U.S. business community to be good
partners."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus submitted its application for EU membership in 1990,
and started its accession negotiations with the EU last March.
</P>
</TEXT>
