<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China, Indonesia to Vie for Uber Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Both defending champions
Indonesia and runners-up China demonstrated superb form when they
won their respective semi-finals at the 17th Uber Cup Badminton
Finals here Thursday, thus setting a championships final clash
between the two Asian badminton arch rivals.
</P>
<P>
Seeking to win back the game's most coveted trophy they had
lost four years ago, China scored an easy 5-0 victory over South
Korea in the first semi-final tie Thursday afternoon in Hong
Kong's Elizabeth Stadium.
</P>
<P>
And Indonesians' 4-1 semi-final triumph over the Danes in the
evening offered a chance to repeat the same rivalry at the last
championships final two years ago at the very same venue.
</P>
<P>
After a record-setting five consecutive victories, China lost
the Uber Cup trophy to Indonesia when conceding 3-2 in the final
in 1994 and again two years later.
</P>
<P>
China qualified for the semi-finals of the current world team
championships after winning Group A with an unbeaten record while
defending champions Indonesia took Group B's top place with three
straight wins.
</P>
<P>
Both China and Indonesia fielded their best line-ups Thursday.
China's fairly easy 5-0 semi-final win over South Korea, which
cost them less than two and a half hours, came out a warm-up
before taking on their Indonesian opponents at Saturday's
championship final.
</P>
<P>
Chinese head coach Li Yongbo said he felt more confident of his
team as well as world number one Ye Zhaoying. "Ye has improved
both mentally and technically. If she plays to her best form
during the final, she will win," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Ye lost to Indonesia's world champion and Olympic gold-medalist
Susi Susanti 2-1 after winning the opening game in the 1996
championships final. Ye has not lost a single game in the current
tournament here.
</P>
<P>
But Susanti had some trouble in her semi-final clash Thursday
evening against Denmark's European champion Camilla Martin, who
upset the Indonesian ace 11-7 in the opening game. But an
experienced Susanti did not give too much chance to her opponent
when she took two consecutive games to seal up a 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
China's world number three Gong Zhichao won over South Korean
Lee Joo Hyun 2-0 in 18 minutes Thursday afternoon. The Chinese was
upset by lowly-rated Japanese Yasuko Mizui 1-2 in a Group A match
four days ago.
</P>
<P>
"We've been giving Gong some special training this week,
including her footwork. She has improved a lot since then, both on
mentality and technique. She is back to her best and confident
today," Li said.
</P>
<P>
"The whole (Chinese) team is getting into the top form," he
added.
</P>
<P>
In the Thomas Cup semi-finals Friday, runners-up Denmark will
play Malaysia in the afternoon and defending champions Indonesia
will take on China in the evening. The championships final is
slated for Sunday evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
