<HEADLINE> Son-in-Law of Iran's Dissident Canonist Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Hadi Hashemi, son-in-law of Iran's
famous dissident religious canonist Ayatollah Hussein Ali
Montazeri, was arrested recently for creating political
disturbance, the evening daily Kayhan reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted an informed source as saying that Hashemi recently
encouraged a group of people to create tension in Isfahan and
Najafabad in the central province of Isfahan. But the paper
did not mention when he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
Following reports about a scheduled demonstration by a group
of people to show their support for Montazeri, Iranian supreme
leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei issued a statement last week,
calling on the people of Isfahan province "to neutralize the
attempts by deceived people."
</P>
<P>
The demonstration was canceled after the people of Isfahan
province turned out to reiterate their loyalty to Khamenei and
condemned any plots against the supreme leader.
</P>
<P>
Montazeri, former designated successor of the late Iranian
supreme leader Imam Khomeini, has been placed under house arrest
in the religious city of Qom since last November after he
challenged the supreme leadership of Khamenei and blamed him for
interference in government affairs.
</P>
<P>
During the past months, many people in Isfahan province,
particularly in Montazeri's hometown Najafabad, expressed
dissatisfaction with the attitude of the authorities toward
Montazeri.
</P>
<P>
Kayhan also said that Hadi Hashemi, then chief of Montazeri's
office, had been arrested in 1986 along with his brother Mehdi
Hashemi for creating confrontation between Montazeri and
Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
Mehdi Hashemi was executed, but Hadi Hashemi was released after
he promised not to intervene in the affairs of Montazeri, who was
also forced to resign as Khomeini's successor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
