<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fu Quanyou Holds Talks With German Military Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Gen. Fu Quanyou, a member of the
Central Military Commission and chief of the General Staff of the
Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA), held talks here today with
Gen. Hartmut Bagger, inspector general of the German Federal
Defense Forces.
</P>
<P>
Fu expressed a warm welcome to Bagger and said that he believed
Bagger's visit is bound to further understanding between the two
countries and their armed forces, and push forward their friendly
relations.
</P>
<P>
Fu said, with joint efforts the exchanges and cooperation in
various sectors between the two countries and their armed forces
have been strengthened continuously, and the PLA is ready to
further advance its friendly and cooperative ties with the German
Federal Defense Forces in the spirit of mutual respect, equality
and benefit.
</P>
<P>
Fu briefed his guest on China's independent foreign policy of
peace, its defence-oriented defence policy and the strategic
principles of active defence, as well as China's views on the
current international situation.
</P>
<P>
With regard to India's recent nuclear tests, Fu noted that
India, by conducting successively five nuclear tests May 11-13,
has ruined the international efforts to bring about a
comprehensive ban on nuclear tests and has met strong protests
from the world community. The Chinese government has expressed its
strong condemnation.
</P>
<P>
India's action, which runs against the historical trend, will
have a serious impact on peace and stability in South Asia and the
world at large, Fu stressed. Some Indians with ulterior motives
advocate the so-called China threat; in fact, they are looking for
an excuse to carry out India's nuclear weapon program, he said.
</P>
<P>
Fu noted that the Chinese armed forces, sticking to the road of
fewer but better troops with Chinese characteristics, is firmly
implementing the strategic decision announced by President Jiang
Zemin to reduce the PLA by another 500,000 personnel within three
years.
</P>
<P>
Bagger said Germany opposes and has condemned India's nuclear
tests, and Germany regards India's move as undermining stability
in the South Asian region.
</P>
<P>
He said his visit to China is short, but he is deeply impressed
by this country and he has changed some of his past views on
China.
</P>
<P>
He added that, although the cultures of Germany and China are
quite different, the two countries can make positive contributions
to guaranteeing lasting peace in the world as long as they enhance
exchanges and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Bagger stressed that Germany and China should not only develop
their economic and political relations, but also develop ties
between their armed forces. He said that he hoped that the armed
forces in the two countries would bolster personnel exchanges,
especially among young officers, so as to develop all-around
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Lieut. Gen. Xiong Guangkai, deputy chief of the PLA General
Staff, and Herbert Jess, minister of the German Embassy in
Beijing, were present at the talks.
</P>
<P>
Bagger arrived in China on May 17 for an official visit as Fu's
guest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
