<HEADLINE> Hamas Leader Visits Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Leader of the Palestinian Islamic
Resistance Movement Hamas Sheikh Ahmed Yassin started on Thursday
a three-day visit to Syria in an effort to unify the Palestinian
groups based here.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Yassin is expected to hold talks with
Syrian leaders on the latest developments of Middle East
situations, and Hamas' attitude towards the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) and the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
He will meet with leaders of the Damascus-based Palestinian
factions to unify the ranks of the Palestinians against the
Israeli intransigence.
</P>
<P>
The visit is aimed at unifying Palestinian groups to confront
Israel, Yassin said, adding that the Palestinians must use force
to retrieve the land the Jewish state took by force.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of restoring the occupied Arab land
and establishing an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The Hamas leader spoke highly of Syria's stand on the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Syria's stand is good and great and no seed of sand will be
ceded to Israel," Yassin said.
</P>
<P>
He is on a tour of Muslim countries. He has visited Egypt,
Saudi Arabia, Qatar, Iran, the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait and
Yemen. He will also travel to Lebanon, Pakistan and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Yassin, a 61-year-old quadriplegic, founded Hamas in 1989. He
was freed by Israel last October after serving 10 years of a life
sentence in an Israeli jail for ordering the killing of
Palestinians who collaborated with Israel. 
</P>
