<HEADLINE> India Wants to Continue Dialogue With China: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Indian official
said Thursday that India wants to continue dialogue and improve
relations with China.
</P>
<P>
Brajesh Mishra, principal secretary of Indian Prime Minister
Atal Behari Vajpayee, said to reporters that both sides should put
aside the statements made against each other over the past few
days and restart the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
In the recent past, Indian Defense Minister George Fernandes
slandered China, calling it the "number one threat" to India.
</P>
<P>
On May 11, when India conducted three nuclear tests, Vajpayee
wrote to leaders of nine countries, referring to China and
Pakistan as a threat to India and the main reason for the nuclear
tests.
</P>
<P>
China has dismissed the statements as groundless.
</P>
<P>
Mishra said that India wants to improve relations with China
through dialogue on various levels as they did before.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Indian ambassador to China would go back to
Beijing within a few days and that his recall had been planned
before the nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the Indian ambassador to China was called
back for consultations due to tense relations between the two
countries following India's nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
He said India also wants to dialogue with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
On the nuclear tests in May 11 and 13, which has caused strong
reactions from the world community, Mishra said that India would
like to propose a unilateral moratorium on its future nuclear
tests and it is prepared for talks with nuclear weapon states to
formalize this obligation. 
</P>
