<HEADLINE> Israel, U.S. Test Missile-Proof Building Materials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel and the United States are
carrying out tests to develop new building materials and equipment
capable of withstanding ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
A report of the Haaretz daily said on Thursday that a test took
place Wednesday in the Negev Desert in southern Israel.
</P>
<P>
The test involved the detonation of a ballistic missile with a
warhead containing a tonne of explosives.
</P>
<P>
A five-story structure was built for the test, using reinforced
concrete for the skeleton and the stairwell.
</P>
<P>
The building had internal shelters built according to
regulations. The test was intended to examine the strength of the
walls, which were built with different types of blocks.
</P>
<P>
The program, which is conducted jointly by the Israeli army and
the U.S. Defense Department, began in 1996. It is aimed at
providing alternatives to sealed rooms and internal shelters that
are mandatory in new apartments in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The tests are financed by the U.S., which supplies
sophisticated measuring devices to gauge the resilience of the
walls and the durability of the blocks during a blast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
