<HEADLINE> Peace Process in W. Sahara Going Well: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Western Saharan envoy Ould-Salek
Salem has delivered a special message from his leader Mafoud Ali
Beiba to OAU Chairman and Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
here, saying the peace process in the territory is going on well.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Herald paper after the meeting
Wednesday, Salem said the message was an appraisal of Mugabe's
work in his capacity as Chairman of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) on the current situation in Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
He said, "as you know, we agreed with Morocco last September
to hold a referendum in Western Sahara under the supervision of
the United Nations. I have come to brief President Mugabe about
the progress that has been made so far in that respect."
</P>
<P>
Salim charged that Morocco intented to bring in its citizens
so that they could take part in the referendum with a view to
influencing the results.
</P>
<P>
"President Mugabe gave assurances that he would ensure that a
free and fair referendum takes place," he said.
</P>
<P>
The vote is to decide whether Western Sahara, a former Spanish
colony, should be incorporated into Morocco, which controls most
of the territory, or become independent, as sought by the
Polisario Front which set up the Saharawi Arab Democratic
People's Republic with Beiba as its President.
</P>
<P>
A U.N.-monitored cease-fire between Polisario and Morocco has
been in force since September 1991 but the referendum has been
repeatedly postponed because of differences over the eligibility
of voters, with Morocco and Polisario accusing each other of
trying to pack the electoral rolls.
</P>
<P>
The referendum, originally set for January 1992, had been time
and again put off till the recently-scheduled date of December 7
this year because lack of progress in resolving issues linked to
the identification of applicants from three disputed tribal
groups.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations moved in last December and set up election
posts to enable the people to vote in a referendum deciding
whether they want total independence from Morocco or not.
</P>
<P>
Salem said the identification of genuine voters has been
proceeding well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
