<HEADLINE> Japan-China Group Raps Controversial Movie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A Japan-China association on Thursday
blasted the controversial Japanese film "Pride -- the Fateful
Moment" which whitewashes Japan's aggression against neighboring
countries during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Hotsuki Ozaki, representative executive of the Japan-China
Cultural Exchange Association, said the movie distorted history
and sanitized Japan's invasion of Asia during the war.
</P>
<P>
"The movie equivocally depicts the Japanese invasion of China
and gives the impression the Nanjing Massacre was a mere
fabrication," Ozaki said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The movie cannot be accepted since it destroys trust of Asian
nations in Japan," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The movie, to be put on show later this month, deals with the
trial and last days of General Hideki Tojo, Japan's wartime prime
minister, who was executed as a Class-A war criminal by the
International Military Tribunal for the Far East in November 1948.
</P>
<P>
It also depicts Japan's aggression against neighboring
countries during World War II as self-defense and denies Japanese
troops' war crimes including the Nanjing Massacre in which about
300,000 people were killed by the Japanese army.
</P>
<P>
The film has drawn criticism from various circles both at home
and abroad since its previews were given last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
