<HEADLINE> Taliban Urge U.N. to Be Impartial in Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Taliban militia
Thursday urged the United Nations to be impartial in mediating
peace talks among warring factions, saying otherwise the world
body can "hardly play any effective role" in resolving the Afghan
issue.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the U.N. proves its impartiality ... it can hardly play
any effective role as mediator, and gain any achievement in
resolving Afghan issues," Taliban's envoy in Pakistan Adul Hakim
Mujahid told reporters here Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban envoy held the rival Northern Alliance "fully
responsible for" the failure of the latest round of Afghan peace
talks, which broke down early this month in Islamabad. The talks,
the first encounter between the Afghan rivals in over a year, were
under the auspices of the U.N. and the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
"The roots of this can be traced in their (the alliance)
negative attitude towards the talks, the internal differences
among the various opposition factions and their benefits from the
continuation of war," he said.
</P>
<P>
Also, he said, the U.N. shall to be blamed "in part" for the
break-up of the talks because it failed to play the role of a
neutral mediator.
</P>
<P>
Despite the request of the Taliban, the U.N. "did not publicize
the original record of the talks," and in its statements, the U.N.
made no mention of the concessions made by the student militia
during the talks, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the U.N. did not criticize the statement made by the
opposition spokesman minutes after the suspension of the talks
which actually announced the agreement over the Ulema (religious
scholars) Commission as void and null, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban envoy's statement came after the U.N. has accused
that the Taliban have abandoned direct talks with the Northern
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. spokesman said in New York Tuesday that the Taliban
leadership has withdrawn a proposal to set up a Ulema Commission
to rule Afghanistan, which is seen as the country's best chance at
peace in decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
