<HEADLINE> Indonesian New President Pledges to Speed Up Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's new President
Bacharuddib Jusuf Habibie pledged here Thursday evening to speed
up reforms in all fields and to form an honest government as early
as possible to meet the aspiration of the people.
</P>
<P>
In a nation-wide television address, Habibie said he needs
support from the whole nation to carry out his duties in
implementing political, economic and legal reforms at the current
difficult time when the country is facing severe political and
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"I deeply concern about the aspiration of the people, including
those from various social circles as well as students and House
members for a total reform in the country. So I will soon set up a
professional cabinet to review the existing laws," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said he will create a clean government without corruption,
nepotism and monopoly.
</P>
<P>
To make the reform a success, Habibie called on the people of
the whole country to unite and avoid confrontation in an effort to
tide over the current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
He also made it clear that the Indonesian government will
implement all agreements it signed with foreign countries
including the reform agreement with the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Habibie, who assumed the presidential office Thursday morning
after Soeharto resigned, also thanked Soeharto for his great
contributions to the country in the past 32 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
