<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Reiterates Support for Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Jordan said on Thursday it firmly
sides with the Palestinians in their peace efforts, especially at
a time when the United States fails to bend Israeli government's
hardline policy.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians enjoy Jordan's support for restoring their
rights and establishing an independent state on their national
soil, Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Salam Majali said after
meeting with Palestinian National Authority's Minister of Planning
and International Cooperation Nabil Shaath.
</P>
<P>
Jordan backs the Palestinians in confronting Israeli
"intransigence" in their peace talks and the stalemate of the
peace process caused by the intransigence, Majali said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Jordan "seeks to use its good relations with all
the concerned parties to put an end to the stalemate created and
imposed by the Israeli government."
</P>
<P>
Shaath, who arrived here on Wednesday for a two-day visit, said
after the meeting that U.S. recent efforts have failed to revive
the long-stalled Palestinian-Israeli peace talks and now the hope
is pinned on the mediation of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been in a deadlock
since March 1997 when Israel broke ground for the construction of
a Jewish settlement in East Arab Jerusalem, which the Palestinians
want as capital of their independent state.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks are also stuck over Israeli troop withdrawal
from the West Bank. The U.S. has reportedly called on Israel to
hand over another 13 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But the Jewish state has rejected the scope, saying it would
endanger its security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
