<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fines, Fees Not to Be Used as Department Expenditures: Wei Jianxing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Imposing fines and collecting
administrative fees must not be regarded as income sources for
jurisdiction, law-enforcement or executive departments, a
high-ranking Chinese official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The income from fines and fees must be put into the state
coffers, and a clear line must be drawn between these incomes and
the expenditures of the departments in charge of the work of
imposing fines or collecting fees," said Wei Jianxing, member of
the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and secretary of the CPC
Central Commission for Discipline Inspection.
</P>
<P>
Wei made the remarks at a national televised conference on
carrying out the concerned regulations. "The separation of
departments' incomes from their expenditures is an important step
for taking precautions against and rooting out corruption," he
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Some departments intercept and hold onto such incomes, which
not only results in a large amount of financial waste but also
creates corruption, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Ministry of Public Security, the Supreme
People's Procuratorate, the Supreme People's Court and the State
Administration of Industry and Commerce to strictly carry out the
regulations.
</P>
<P>
"No one and no work unit is allowed to divert or withhold such
funds, and systems should be established to strengthen their
management," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, governments at all levels should also strictly
adhere to the CPC Central Committee's instructions, he said,
adding quotas are by no means allowed to be imposed on departments
concerned for the incomes from fines and fee collections.
</P>
<P>
Luo Gan, member of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central
Committee, member of the secretariat of the CPC Central Committee,
and secretary of the Central Political Science and Law Committee
presided over the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
