<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Call For Better Protection of Rare Dolphins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Two leading scientists with the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) have urged relevant departments
to ensure better protection for the white-flag dolphin, which is a
more endangered species than the panda.
</P>
<P>
Academicians of CAS Liu Jiankang and Chen Yiyu suggested that
moving white-flag dolphins from their original habitat to a nature
reserve would be the ideal way to protect them.
</P>
<P>
China is the only country which has the most endangered species
of dolphin in the world, with fewer than 100 living on the middle
and lower reaches of the Yangtze River, said Liu, a professor at
the Research Institute of Aquatic Animals and Plants.
</P>
<P>
The number of such dolphins is shrinking due to the rapid
development of fishing, shipping, water conservancy and
environmental pollution on the river, Liu said, adding that more
than 90 percent of the deaths of white-flag dolphins are due to
such factors.
</P>
<P>
He said that since these adverse factors cannot be eradicated
in the short term, the only way out is to move the dolphins to a
nature reserve which has a similar natural environment as their
original habitat.
</P>
<P>
Liu and other scientists at the institute have tried to raise
black finless porpoises, which have similar habits to white-flag
dolphins, in the Tian'e Zhou River at Shishou City, in central
China's Hubei Province, and found the area suitable for raising
dolphins.
</P>
<P>
They have delivered a report about setting up a nature reserve
for white-flag dolphins in the area to the State Council, and have
already received approval.
</P>
<P>
Liu suggested that the Ministry of Agriculture should organize
a special team to remove the dolphins to the area, and provide
sufficient funds for the management of the nature reserve.
</P>
<P>
He said the state should ban fishing totally from the area and
arrange other jobs for local fishermen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
