<HEADLINE> Radar Introduced in Air-Control Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A majority of China's air-control
areas have introduced radar management systems, according to
sources at the Air Traffic Management Bureau (ATMB) of the Civil
Aviation Administration of China.
</P>
<P>
Radar equipment allows access to high-accuracy flight information,
including flight conditions, location and height, which enables
precise directions to be given.
</P>
<P>
China has built and upgraded a number of regional airport air
control centers in recent years, as well as 247 flight information
terminals, said Zhou A'rong, deputy director of the ATMB.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that computer and new telecommunications technology
has now been applied in civil aviation management, covering
aircraft departure, and fuel and income management.
</P>
<P>
This has greatly increased flight punctuality, service
quality and passenger safety, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
