<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen to Help 21,000 Jobless Find Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- This, China's first special
economic zone, plans to help more than half of its 15,000 workers
laid off by state-owned enterprises and 12,500 jobless people find
jobs this year.
</P>
<P>
The plan was announced today at a meeting of Shenzhen officials
to discuss how to address the unemployment problem. Shenzhen Mayor
Li Zibin will head the city's re-employment work group.
</P>
<P>
Li announced that Shenzhen will help all workers laid off by
state-owned enterprises to become re-employed within three years,
while making sure that the number getting re-employed surpasses
those being laid off.
</P>
<P>
The mayor said that Shenzhen will set up a re-employment
service center to organize training and job introduction.
</P>
<P>
The city will also institute a fund to provide basic living
expenses and finance training programs for workers laid off by
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen will gather 20 million yuan for the fund this year,
and it should grow at an annual rate of ten percent, Li said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
