<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Leaders Meet in Kremlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko and chairmen of the upper and
lower houses of parliament Yegor Stroyev and Gennady Seleznyov
agreed Thursday that all branches of power should work together to
overcome the difficulties the country is experiencing.
</P>
<P>
The "big four" of Russia held a 75-minute meeting in the
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Stroyev and Seleznyov told reporters that no
one should think there are differences between the government and
the parliament in assessing the present situation.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov said they informed the president of their concerns
over the country's future.
</P>
<P>
Stroyev described the current situation in Russia as "acute,"
adding that "anything may follow (ongoing) strikes by coal miners,
students and school teachers."
</P>
<P>
The four leaders also agreed to hold an "anti-crisis meeting"
in early June.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's meeting was also attended by Valentin Yumashev, head
of the Presidential Administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
