<HEADLINE> China's B-Share Market Expected to Bottom Out (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The bearish Chinese B-share market
is expected to gain lost ground and embark on an upward trend in
the near future, according to messages from the authorities and
predictions of stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
The China Securities Regulatory Commission (CSRC) is looking
into the problems with the nation's hard currency stock
market and will do its best to solve them, declared Chen Yaoxian,
vice-chairman of the CSRC.
</P>
<P>
"Compared to the active A-share market, the B-share market has
been failing the investors' expectations," Chen admitted,
adding, "We still take a positive attitude toward the B-share
market, and we are full of confidence in its future."
</P>
<P>
"The B-share market will see accelerated development very
soon," Chen stressed.
</P>
<P>
The B-share stock markets in Shanghai and Shenzhen have been
stranded in a downward trend since 1992. The sharpest decline
since then stood at 72.7 percent and 81.15 percent for the two
markets, respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, there seems to be no doubt that the B-share market, a
hard currency stock market targeting overseas investors, will
continue to act as an offshore capital market for domestic
enterprises until the RMB yuan becomes fully convertible.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing basically wrong with the B-share market, and
the system is capable of raising a substantial amount of money for
China," said Gary Coull, chairman and CEO of Credit Lyonnais
Securities Ltd. "The B-share market has been severely bearish
since there are so many choices of different ways to play China,
and B-share companies are facing competition from companies listed
on better-regulated overseas markets, such as red chips, H-share
companies and N-share companies."
</P>
</TEXT>
