<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Exports increase 10 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Australian exports increased 10
percent in 1997 over 1996, with manufactured goods leading the
way, a study on Australia trade released Thursday said.
</P>
<P>
Composition of Trade 1997, released by the Department of
Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT), revealed that exports increased
by 10 percent last year to 85 billion Australian dollars (54
billion U.S. dollars), while imports increased by six percent to
83 billion Australian dollars (52.7 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 2.3 billion Australian dollars surplus was a major
improvement compared with the previous year's 0.8 billion trade
deficit.
</P>
<P>
Japan was once again Australia's single biggest market, taking
20 percent or 16.8 billion Australian dollars (10.67 billion U.S.
dollars) of Australia's exports, an increase of eight percent from
the figures in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Next were South Korea with 6.8 billion Australian dollars and
the United States with 6.3 billion Australian dollars (4.3 and 4.0
billion U.S. dollars respectively).
</P>
<P>
The Asia Pacific region took a massive 71 percent of
Australia's exports, with growth in Asia alone registering 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
However, trade figures released Thursday for the first quarter
of this year showed a dramatic slump in Australian exports,
especially to Asia.
</P>
<P>
Exports to every major country in Asia were down in the first
quarter, while the exports to the United States increased to
account for 13 percent of the Australian exports due to the fall
in the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, coal was Australia's single biggest export, rising 13
percent to 8.8 billion Australian dollars (5.9 billion U.S.
dollars), which accounts more than 10 percent of the total
exports.
</P>
<P>
Australia's reputation as a quarry and a farm for the world is
being rendered out of date by the growth in manufactured exports,
which now account for 33 percent of total exports up from 28
percent just five years earlier.
</P>
<P>
However, exports of the traditional staples, wheat and wool,
increased by more than 10 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
On the import side, the United States remains the single
biggest source, supplying a massive 22 percent of the overseas
goods, followed by Japan which supplied 12 percent of imports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
