<HEADLINE> Seminar on China's Economic Development Held </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of non-communist
parties in China were invited to air their views on the country's
present economic situation and future development under the
influence of Southeast Asian financial crisis at a seminar held
here today.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was co-organized by the United Front Work
Department (UFWD) of the Central Committee of the Communist Party
of China, central committees of all non-communist parties in China
and the All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the seminar, Wang Zhaoguo, head of the UFWD, said
the move was to enable people to have a correct understanding of
China's current economic situation and strengthen their confidence
of overcoming difficulties so as to effect a sustained, rapid and
steady growth of China's economy.
</P>
<P>
He urged all participants to put forward their valuable
suggestions on improving reforms, opening-up and the modernization
drive.
</P>
<P>
Participants say that China's policies and principles so far
adopted are entirely correct, but they all hold that the Southeast
Asian financial crisis is not yet over and great effort should
continue to reduce its impact on China to the minimum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
