<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Reap Rice Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Agricultural
Minister has predicted a rice harvest in the country this season
despite the negative effects by floods over the past months.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper Thursday quoted Paul Kimiti, Minister
of Agriculture and Cooperatives, as saying that the government is
likely to allow traders to export the rice if an assessment
presently underway proves that Tanzania is going to have enough
rice stocks.
</P>
<P>
However, the government will be unable to transport food in
stocks from harvest areas to those which suffer from food
shortage due to damaged roads, the minister said in the
Sumbawanga District Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa said earlier this year Tanzania needed more
than 100 million U.S. Dollars to repair damaged roads and other
infrastructure facilities.
</P>
<P>
The east African country banned food exports a few years ago
after food stocks were exhausted.
</P>
<P>
The report further said during the current season, rains
blamed on El Nino devastated farms and caused an outbreak of
rodent invasion unseen in the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has spent 200 million Shillings
(about 325,000 U.S. Dollars) to fight the crop eating bird of
quelea quelea which invaded a lot of farms in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
