<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Govt Committed to Civil Service Integrity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Anson Chan, secretary for
administration of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR), stressed here Thursday the government's firm commitment
to upholding Hong Kong Civil servants' fine tradition of
integrity.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of a seminar on "Hong Kong into the
21st Century -- Maintaining Integrity in the Civil Service", Chan
said that the Hong Kong Civil Service enjoys a well-deserved but
hard earned reputation among the local and international community
for its efficiency and honesty.
</P>
<P>
"Our high standard of probity and performance are acknowledged
to be among the key advantages that have secured Hong Kong's very
high position in the global league of the best places to live and
to invest and work," she said. "but we cannot afford to be
complacent."
</P>
<P>
Over 190,000 strong, the Civil Service is the single largest
group of employers in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural policy address last October, Chief Executive
Tung Chee Hwa affirmed the commitment of the Civil Service to
serve the community through the proper exercise of its powers and
the faithful discharge of its responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
Chan said the responsive government which the Chief Executive
described needs a Civil Service which adheres to a set of shared
values.
</P>
<P>
These values can best be summed up in six key principles of
commitment to the rule of law; honesty and integrity above private
interests; accountability and openness in decision-making and in
all actions; political neutrality in conducting official duties;
impartiality in the execution of public functions; and dedication
and diligence in serving the community, she said.
</P>
<P>
Over 300 senior civil servants from about 90 bureaus and
departments attended the seminar which was jointly organized by
the Civil Service Bureau and the Independent Commission Against
Corruption.
</P>
<P>
After the seminar, Lily Yam Kwan Pui-ying, commissioner of the
Independent Commission Against Corruption, and Lam Woon-kwong,
secretary for the Civil Service, gave a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Yam revealed that corruption reports against the police dropped
by five percent in the first four months of this year compared
with the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Reports against other government departments rose slightly from
255 to 269 in the same period, she said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if there had been any change in the pattern of corruption
since the handover, Yam said that it remained very much the same
and that Hong Kong's corruption figures were comparatively low.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
