<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Secretary for Treasury to Attend APEC Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Secretary for the Treasury Denise
Yue of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China
will depart Friday for Canada for the Fifth Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) Finance Ministers Meeting (FMM).
</P>
<P>
Yue will lead an eight-member delegation, with representatives
from the Finance Bureau, the Financial Services Bureau and the
Hong Kong Monetary Authority, to the FMM, which is scheduled to be
held in Kananaskis, Alberta, between May 22 and 24.
</P>
<P>
The APEC Finance Ministers will discuss financial and economic
events in the APEC region, with a particular emphasis on the
recent financial instability and ways to strengthen domestic and
international financial systems.
</P>
<P>
Discussion items include encouraging the recovery of private
capital flows to Asia, the Year 2000 problem, strengthening the
international financial architecture and domestic financial
systems, and enhancing
macroeconomic and financial surveillance.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, to be chaired by Canada's Financial Minister Paul
Martin, will bring together Ministers and delegations from the 18
APEC members.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from the Asian Development Bank, the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank will also
participate in the meeting. In addition, the Finance Ministers
will exchange views with private sector financiers from the APEC
economies.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return to China on July 1, 1997, it remains a
full member of the APEC by the name of Hong Kong, China.
</P>
<P>
The 18 APEC member economies are Australia; Brunei Darussalam;
Canada; Chile; China; Hong Kong, China; Indonesia; Japan; the
Republic of Korea; Malaysia; Mexico; New Zealand; Papua New
Guinea; the Philippines; Singapore; Chinese Taipei; Thailand; and
the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
