<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Failed TV License Bidders to Sue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Two bidders which failed to
win South Africa's first private free-to-air television license
earlier this year will sue the authority body involved for its
"unfair" decision, local media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two consortiums, Free to Air and New Channel TV, said
Wednesday they will apply to the high court for a review of the
decision of the Independent Broadcasting Authority (IBA), which
oversees the nation's broadcast services, to grant the license to
Midi Television.
</P>
<P>
The two top bidders, among the six failed bidders, argue that
Midi is not the most suitable applicant and there were
"procedural irregularities" in the granting process.
</P>
<P>
Despite the court action threat, Midi Television said Thursday
it will begin broadcasting on October 1, and become virtually
the first competitor of the now dominating state TV operator, the
South African Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The IBA said Wednesday it intended to stand by its decision
and was confident it conducted the process in a fair and
transparent way.
</P>
<P>
The IBA also said the pending action is "quite exciting" as
it will help "build jurisprudence around broadcasting
regulation."
</P>
<P>
Revealing the reasons for its decision last month, the IBA
said Midi's corporate status and strong black empowerment
ownership gave it the "competitive edge."  
</P>
</TEXT>
