<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Destroy Outdated Farm Chemicals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique is to burn up about 2.5
million tons of outdated agricultural chemicals, an official with
the Ministry of Agriculture and Fishery said here.
</P>
<P>
The outdated chemicals have been collected from 60 stores and
over 500 grass-roots points throughout the country, said Martina
Pancas, Chief of the Plant Sanitation Department with the
Ministry Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official said that some of the chemicals have been stored
for over 20 years and are expired and posing as contamination for
environment, Noticias reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture ministry is, according to a government
initiative, shifting out the chemicals that are still effective
and destroy all those outdated.
</P>
<P>
The initiative to destroy outdated farm chemicals, which
started in 1994, is to end in September this year, with a
financial aid of about six million U.S. Dollars from Denmark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
