<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Final Members of Cambodia's Constitutional Council Named </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The last three members of
Cambodia's nine-member Constitutional Council were appointed
Thursday by the Supreme Council of Magistracy.
</P>
<P>
They were chosen from seven candidates at a three-hour meeting
of the Supreme Council chaired by Chea Sim, president of National
Assembly and acting head of state.
</P>
<P>
The list is yet to be approved by King Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Council is empowered to review laws passed
by the National Assembly and to rule on election disputes,
including interpretation of election results. General elections
are scheduled for July 26.
</P>
<P>
The king and the National Assembly have each appointed their
three respective representatives on the Constitutional Council.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the king's three, the rest come from Cambodia's
People's Party (CPP).
</P>
<P>
The three members named by the Supreme Council are Chan Sok,
president of the Supreme Court, Prak Sok, secretary of state at
the Ministry of Public Works and Thor Peng Leath, former governor
of the National Bank.
</P>
<P>
Oppositions and legal experts have criticized the formation of
the council as hasty.
</P>
<P>
"The council is being formed in a hasty and irregular manner
that will impair its function and put its legitimacy in question,"
said Chau Sen Cocsal Chhum, the most senior appointee to the
council named by the King.
</P>
<P>
"If the formation of the council proceeds as planned and the
election date stands at July 26, the council will be unable to
properly perform its duties to ensure an election that is valid
under the Constitution," he said in a statement Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
