<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Bank Partners Announce Huge Community Development Lending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Merger partners NationsBank and
BankAmerica Wednesday announced a commitment of 350 billion
U.S. dollars over the next decade for low-and-moderate-income
customers, including mortgages and loans to minority applicants.
</P>
<P>
In a joint release, both banks called it the largest, most
comprehensive program of its kind.
</P>
<P>
The 350-billion-dollar commitment includes specific lending and
investment goals for affordable housing, small business, consumer
lending and economic development. As part of the commitment, the
new company pledges to acquire, build or rehabilitate 50,000
affordable housing units during the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Of the money, 180 billion dollars for small businesses will
include conventional and government-assisted loans, as well as
investment in small business investment corporations and minority
business venture capital funds.
</P>
<P>
The affordable housing program with 115 billion dollars
includes single- and multi-family lending and investment to low-
and moderate income borrowers and minority applicants.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five billion dollars for economic development include
loans and investments to nonprofit organizations such as community
development corporations.
</P>
<P>
Thirty billion dollars for consumer loans include home-related
loans for borrowers below median income and other auto and
consumer loans for borrowers with an annual household income at or
below 80 percent of median income. Credit card borrowing is not
included in this commitment.
</P>
<P>
Last month, NationsBank and BankAmerica announced a
57.2-billion-dollar marriage to create a coast-to-coast banking
behemoth. The new company will have about 180,000 employees and
offices in the country's 22 states. The new bank will become the
country's leader in home mortgage lending to minority and low- and
moderate-income borrowers as well as small businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
