<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Increases Credit Financing Facilities to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim announced here Thursday to double the
country's export credit financing facilities to 4 billion ringgit
(1.0666 billion U.S. dollars) with immediate effect to promote
exports.
</P>
<P>
Of the 4 billion ringgit, 3 billion ringgit ( 0.8 billion U.S.
dollars) would be allocated for the Export Credit Refinancing
(ECR) scheme, up 1.7 billion ringgit ( 453.333 million U.S.
dollars) from the present level of 1.3 billion ringgit (346.666
million U.S. dollars), Anwar, who is also finance minister, said
at a press conference here after chairing a meeting with bank
officials and exporters to discuss additional allocation for
export credit.
</P>
<P>
The other 1 billion ringgit (266.666 million U.S. dollars) is
allocated for the supplier credit, buyer credit and overseas
investment credit facilities being managed by the Export-Import
Bank (Exim Bank), he said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that the facilities have proven to be effective in
promoting exports. In recognizing the important role that trading
companies play in marketing and promoting exports of Malaysian
goods, the ECR scheme would also be extended to these trading
companies, he added.
</P>
<P>
The ECR facility, being managed by Exim Bank, is made available
to all banks in the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that with increased globalization, countries have
become more vulnerable to external shocks, and competition has
been heightened in the light of the East Asian crisis with all
countries in the region striving to expand through an
export-oriented strategy.
</P>
<P>
He said the facilities were made available by the government to
assist exporters in export promotion efforts.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister called upon exporters to put in more
efforts in undertaking the necessary structural changes themselves
to adapt to the changing competitive environment so as to be
well-positioned to face increased global competition.
</P>
<P>
"They have to be more aggressive in their marketing efforts and
increase exports, not only extending their market share in
existing markets but also through penetrating new markets," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The export-oriented strategies have been a cornerstone of
Malaysia's industrialization strategy and in the present
environment, strong export growth has become even more important
in reducing the country's vulnerability and contributing to
economic recovery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
