<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Kenyans Suffer as Lake Victoria Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Xu Jianmei)
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Fear and panic are gripping
south-western Kenyan region ashore Lake Victoria as its waters
have continued rising since last week, wreaking havoc and
displacing hundreds of people.
</P>
<P>
Families are stranded with no food, livestock trapped and
drowned in the floods and crops ruined.
</P>
<P>
Villages and schools have been swept away and other houses
submerged as the lake waters engulf the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of acres of farmland, mainly under maize, sorghum and
sugarcane, are flooded with the crops destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government on Wednesday announced plans to evacuate
families ashore Lake Victoria, the second largest fresh water
lake in the world.
</P>
<P>
But efforts by the Kenyan government to rescue the displaced
have been hampered by poor roads, which were made impassable by
the floods, while the lack of communication also worsens the
situation.
</P>
<P>
All telephone lines in government offices in the affected
areas have been disconnected over unpaid phone bills and thus
"has made it difficult to monitor the situation and file an
accurate report," said an official in Kisumu, the largest city
ashore the lake.
</P>
<P>
Now rivers of Nyando, Sondu-Miriu, Yala and Nzoia, with the
help of their tributaries, have swept into the lake large amounts
of silt and vegetation from the catchment areas of the western
highlands.
</P>
<P>
From Osodo Bay to Winam Gulf, the land is flooded, a field
report from the Daily Nation newspaper confirmed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
As the water rises, villagers -- many of them fishermen --
have fled to safer and drier land, leaving their homes and
possessions covered in a thick layer of marshland vegetation,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
Many grass-thatched houses collapsed, their soaked mud walls
crumbling and bringing down the roofs. The floated carcasses of
drowned animals drifted slowly on the flood waters between tall
trees, as patient vultures circled above.
</P>
<P>
Men, women and children carrying a few belongings on their
heads, waded through the waist-high waters to safety.
</P>
<P>
The flooding has raised fears of disease. Last year,
water-borne diseases such as typhoid, cholera and diarrhoea swept
across the region, claiming scores of lives.
</P>
<P>
The lake supports some 25 million people, 10 million being in
Kenya, although it only holds about six percent of the lake's
2,760 cubic km of water with Tanzania 49 percent and Uganda 45
percent.
</P>
<P>
The floods have also sparked heated debate about its causes
with some experts arguing the phenomenon, last seen in early
1960s, is mainly a result of siltation due to the blockage of
river estuaries by the hyacinth weed.
</P>
<P>
The blockage by water hyacinth forced silt deposits in the
shallow sections of the lake, damming the rivers and causing
floods, says William Saina, an agricultural expert.
</P>
<P>
He attributed more siltation to destruction of trees and
cultivation in water catchment areas in highlands near the Rift
Valley province.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, a marine expert, Joseph Mucuthi, also said the
hyacinth weed runs riot with roots and leaves having collected at
the bottom of the lake, making it shallower, hence the overflow.
</P>
<P>
Another reason is the shoreline "which is now shrinking
towards the lake" as it has not been surveyed for more than 50
years, Mucuthi said.
</P>
<P>
However, Dr Geoffrey Howard of the International Union for
Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources said Monday the
hyacinth invasion is an unlikely cause of the water rise as 92
percent of the weed is water.
</P>
<P>
"Rainfall increase might be the cause, that is, if the totals
are abnormally high as the one experienced in 1960," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
Water hyacinth is likely to increase the rate of evaporation
hence decreasing water levels, he argued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
