<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh EPZs Attract 293 Million Dollars of Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Companies from other countries and
regions as well as Bangladesh have so far invested 293.29 million
U.S. dollars in Bangladesh's two existing export processing zones
(EPZs), a press release of the Bangladesh EPZ Authority reaching
here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Of the figure, the investment in the Chittagong EPZ stood at
217.23 million dollars and that of the Dhaka EPZ 76.06 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is the biggest investor, and at present, 21 South
Korean businesses with an investment of 72.6 million dollars are
operating in the Chittagong EPZ while another 10 businesses are in
the offing.
</P>
<P>
In the Dhaka EPZ, 13 South Korean businesses are in operation
while another 10 projects are under construction, and the South
Korean companies have invested 40.65 million dollars in this EPZ.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the second biggest investor with an investment of
55.66 million dollars, followed by Bangladesh with 47.27 million
dollars, and the U.S. with 12.88 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Chittagong EPZ became operational in 1983 while the Dhaka
EPZ was commissioned in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In the Chittagong and Dhaka EPZs, there are altogether 113
businesses in operation producing electrical and electronic goods,
garments, fishing reel, golf equipment, textiles, terrytowel,
metal products, plastic goods, footwear, leather goods, furniture,
caps, tents and toys.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government is now planning to set up three more
EPZs in the country to meet the increasing demand from domestic
and foreign investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
