<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Share prices rose sharply on the
Singapore market after Soeharto announced his resignation from
presidency on Thursday, as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index (STII) shot up by 45.87 points to close at 1319.65 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that stock prices surged in an active session. The
resignation of Indonesian President Soeharto drew short-term funds
back to the market, they said.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased to 395.19 million units,
valued at 451.4 million Singapore dollars (about 275.24 million
U.S. dollars). Advances overwhelmed declines by 319 to 30, while
243 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
RHB Capital warrant99 was the most actively traded counter as
it registered a turnover of 37.51 million units. It was followed
by Malaya Resources which had 28.74 million shares traded. Renong
was next with 27.03 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Local computer sound card maker Creative 50 led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 90 cents to finish at 31.8 Singapore
dollars. Jurong Shipyard increased by 75 cents to end at 7.7
Singapore dollars. SPH (Singapore Press Holdings) was up by 60
cents to close at 14.6 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Ho Msia was the biggest loser as it declined
by one dollar to end at 16.5 Singapore dollars. UOI fell by 25
cents to close at 1.6 Singapore dollars, while Hong Leong
Industries was down by 24 cents to finish at 1.8 Singapore
dollars. 
</P>
