<HEADLINE> Tokyo Hopes Jakarta Will Continue Economic Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto said Thursday Japan hopes Indonesia will continue
economic reform under the leadership of new President Bacharuddin
Jusuf Habibie.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, in a statement released soon after Indonesian
President Suharto announced his resignation earlier in the day,
pledged Japan's continued support for Indonesia's reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
"I hope from the bottom of my heart Indonesia will achieve
social stability and economic recovery as early as possible,"
Hashimoto said.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto also expressed the hope that the situation in
Indonesia will calm down, making it possible for Japanese
businessmen to return without fear.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi also said in a statement that
Japan will "continue giving every support possible" to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, which maintains strong economic ties with Tokyo, is
the main recipient of official development assistance from Japan,
totaling 215.2 billion yen (about 1.6 billion U.S. dollars) in
1997.  
