<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Guinea Bissau to Tighten Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and Guinea Bissau have
agreed to further promote bilateral and sub-regional cooperation,
especially in the field of energy.
</P>
<P>
To this end, a meeting of the Nigeria-Guinea Bissau Joint
Commission is to be held in the Nigerian capital Abuja next
month.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting will discuss economic and social
issues that will deepen the good relations between the two
countries and, particularly, the current energy problem in west
Africa to find an early solution.
</P>
<P>
These are the highlights of a communique issued Wednesday at
the end of the two-day visit to Nigeria by President Joao Bernado
Vierra of Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Vierra and his Nigerian counterpart General
Sani Abacha reviewed the progress made in the implementation of
the various cooperation agreements between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging the need to increase the present level of
economic ties between the two countries, the leaders explored new
ways of forging closer and more rewarding collaboration and
reaffirmed the need for regular and sustained contacts and
consultations at various levels.
</P>
<P>
They also reaffirmed their commitment to the objectives and
principles of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), in which their countries are founding members.
</P>
<P>
The leaders renewed their commitment to rapid economic
integration in the sub-region while appealing to member states to
demonstrate the political will to accelerate various ECOWAS
agreements and protocols.
</P>
<P>
As ECOWAS leaders, Abacha and Vierra reaffirmed their
commitment to the use of dialogue and consultations in resolving
conflicts and maintenance of peace and security in the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
They consequently appealed for the reinforcement of the
mechanism for the prevention of conflicts and maintenance of
peace in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Within the wide context of African economic integration, the
two leaders called on all the members of the Organization of
African Unity to take necessary measures at national, regional
and continental levels to ensure effective economic cooperation
among groupings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
