<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel's Relay Baton Passed onto Non-Founding Member </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Craig Barrett, a 24-year
veteran of Intel Corp., Wednesday took over the chip giant's helm
and became its first chief executive officer who was not there at
the founding.
</P>
<P>
Formerly the company's vice president and chief operating
officer, Barrett took the relay baton from Andrew Grove, who
relinquished his title as CEO but will remain chairman.
</P>
<P>
The transition comes as Intel faces diminished profits and
increased competition. Last month the company reported its worst
financial performance in 10 years and said it would eliminate
3,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
At Wednesday's annual shareholders meeting, Barrett reiterated
the company's plan to tackle the industry-wide personal computer
showdown by diversifying its microprocessors to serve different
segments of the market and investing in manufacturing and research
and development.
</P>
<P>
"We need to renew and sustain our historic growth," he told
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
Intel supplies 85 percent of the world's computers with
microprocessors, which function as the brains of the system. The
company's profits and revenues have remained flat for the last 18
months, due to competition from small rivals and slackening of
demand for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
Its revenues for 1997 came roughly to 25 billion U.S. dollars
and profits to 6.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts describe Barrett, 58, as a master planner. He has been
running Intel's day-to-day operations for quite a long time. He is
credited with revamping the manufacturing operations in the 1980s,
making Intel's efficiency the envy of the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
