<HEADLINE> Iran's New Party Calls for Solidarity, Prosperity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran's first political party since
the 1979 Islamic Revolution, the Constructive Executives of Iran
(ECI), Thursday vowed to work for "Islamic Dignity, Sustaining
Construction and Iran's Prosperity."
</P>
<P>
The new party, which came into being Wednesday after being
permitted by the Interior Ministry, called on Iranian people,
especially the young generation, to join hands to build a more
vigorous Iran, according to the Hamshahri daily.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the paper, the party pledged its
commitment to upholding the two principles of Islamism and
Republicanism of the country.
</P>
<P>
As a moderate party, the ECI also expressed its "determined
support" for the government led by moderate President Mohammad
Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Another moderate daily Iran News reported Wednesday that the
ECI would start its political activities "as a full-fledged
political party" with Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi, a close
ally of Khatami, as its secretary general.
</P>
<P>
The ECI was evolved from G-6, originally a political group
founded in 1996 by six technocrats, including Karbaschi.
</P>
<P>
The group played a significant role in the presidential
elections in May last year, in which Khatami won with a landslide
victory.
</P>
<P>
The birth of the ECI may indicate a breakthrough in Iran's
politics because political parties had been banned in the country,
according to analysts here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
