<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise For Fourth Straight Day in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose for four trading
days in a row in Tokyo Thursday, in the wake of Indonesian
President Suharto's resignation.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange advanced 192.30 points or 1.23
percent from Wednesday's close to finish at 15,845.25.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, surged 6.67 points or 0.54 percent to 1,232.29.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the major section grew to an estimated 470 million shares
from Wednesday's 430 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was Thursday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the Tokyo market was backed by the yen's strengthening
against the U.S. dollar to the 135 yen level from Wednesday's 136 yen
level.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Indonesian Vice President Bacharuddin Jusuf Habibie
was sworn in Thursday to replace Suharto, alleviating fears that the
country's turmoil will again weigh on the Japanese economy, they said.
</P>
<P>
Stocks gained ground almost across the board. Of the 1,331 issues
listed on the First Section, gainers outnumbered losers 841 to 315,
with 118 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
