<HEADLINE> South Korea Launches Seventh Submarine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean Navy launched its
seventh 1,200-ton submarine Thursday at the country's southern
island of Koje.
</P>
<P>
Christened "Lee Sun-sin-ham," the diesel-powered submarine is
part of a Navy program that will build nine 209-class submarines
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Armed with torpedos and mines, the submarine, with a 40-member
crew, can cruise at the maximum speed of 22 knots, said the navy.
</P>
<P>
The sub, which will be officially commissioned after a one-year
trial cruise, was named after a 15th century admiral Lee Sun-sin
who as a deputy for the national hero Adm. Yi Sun-sin, expelled
the invading Japanese armada in the South Sea.
</P>
<P>
Under a new submarine project, codenamed SSU, the Navy plans to
make three 1,500-ton submarines armed with Harpoon antiship
missiles, said a navy spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
