<HEADLINE> Zambia to Release $30 Million to Stabilize Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government will release
30 million U.S. Dollars this week to stabilize the foreign exchange
market, said Financial Minister Edith Nawakwi.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Thursday quoted the minister as saying that
the government has already off-loaded more than 50 million
dollars on to the market since the shortage of foreign exchange
started a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange to be released on the market will come
from the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), the country's
main foreign exchange earner, Nawakwi said.
</P>
<P>
The additional release this week will offset the period of
time it took for the donors to start disbursing the 531 million
dollars pledged at the consultative group meeting held in Paris
last week, she said.
</P>
<P>
It took the World Bank two weeks and the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) three weeks to get approval from their boards
of directors before they could start to disburse the money.
</P>
