<HEADLINE> New Chief Minister Named for Malaysia's Sabah State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Malaysian
government has named Bernard Dompok, 49, as new chief minister of
Sabah, East Malaysia, representing the state's non-Muslim
Bumiputra (aboriginals) community.
</P>
<P>
Dompok, who is state Tourism and Environment Minister and Parti
Demokratik Sabah (PDS) president, will succeed Yong Teck Lee,
whose term as chief minister expires on May 28.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim made the
announcement at a press conference here Thursday, saying "I've
been asked by Prime Minister (Mahathir Mohamad) to announce the
name of the new Sabah chief minister to succeed Yong Teck Lee and
he is Bernard Dompok."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir is recuperating at the Universiti Kebangsaan Hospital
here after last week's minor ankle surgery and is resting upon
doctor's orders.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said "He (Dompok) will hold talks with the prime minister
at the earliest possible time before taking his oath of office and
forming the state cabinet."
</P>
<P>
The appointment of a non-Muslim Bumiputra (aboriginal) as chief
minister Thursday has fulfilled Mahathir's pledge to the people of
Sabah in 1994 that the post would be rotated for two years each
among Sabah's three majority communities -- Muslim Bumiputras,
Chinese and non-Muslim Bumiputras.
</P>
<P>
Sabah, one of the two states in East Malaysia, is the only
state where a rotation system is implemented by Mahathir-led
Barisan National (BN) (National Front).
</P>
<P>
The first chief minister under the rotation system came from
the Muslim Bumiputra community followed by Yong, representing the
Chinese. 
</P>
</TEXT>
