<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Energy Production Down in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- China's energy output amounted to
244 million tons of standard coal equivalent during the first
quarter this year, down 9.3 percent over the same period in 1997,
according to the latest statistics from State Statistical Bureau
(SSB).
</P>
<P>
This declining trend is slowed down in last March, when the
year-on-year decrease margin narrowed to 3.8 percent, with the
energy output hitting 97.28 million tons of standard coal
equivalent.
</P>
<P>
In the January-March period, China produced 231 million tons of
crude coal, down 13.9 percent from the figure in the same 1997
period. Meanwhile, the January-March oil output stood at 39.45
million tons, down 0.6 percent. The natural gas output was 5.64
billion cubic meters, down 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to SSB release, Shanxi, Shandong and Inner Mongolia
ranked the top three coal producers in first quarter, with their
coal output reaching 64.95 million tons, 20.21 million tons and
13.19 million tons, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the figures in the same 1997 period, the coal
output for Shanxi and Shandong dropped by 23.41 percent and 7.43
percent, respectively, while that of inner Mongolia going up by
6.49 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's power output reached 266.4 billion kwh in first
quarter, up 1.8 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
