<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Closer to Winning Back Uber Cup Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Losing finalists for the past two
consecutive championships, the Chinese women's badminton team got
one step closer to winning back the game's most coveted trophy
Uber Cup after their semi-final victory at the 17th Uber Cup
Badminton Finals here Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
With the 5-0 victory over South Korea Thursday morning, the
Chinese are to play in Saturday's final the winners of the other
semi-final between defending champions Indonesia and Denmark,
which was scheduled for Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
China had been the runners-up for the 1994 and 1996
championships after five consecutive victories in the bilateral
tournament. It qualified for the semi-finals of the current world
team championships after winning the four-team Group A as its top
finishers with an unbeaten record on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
China fielded its best ever line-up on Thursday. The fairly
easy semi-final victory over South Korea came out of a warm-up for
the Chinese before taking on their opponents at the final on
Friday, most probably defending champions Indonesia. The victory
over South Korea cost the Chinese less than two and a half hours.
</P>
<P>
China's world number Gong Zhichao, whose 2-1 upset last Sunday
by 31st-ranked Japanese Yasuko Mizui became the tournament's
biggest surprise, defeated South Korea's Lee Kyung won 11-4, 11-0
in just 18 minutes on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chinese head coach Li Yongbo said the 20-year-old still needed
some encouragement to be fully recovered from the defeat. "And we
helped her to improve her footwork as well," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li said he was happy with the team's performance on Thursday.
