<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Yellow River Delta Looking For Faster Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- After years of agricultural
development, China's Yellow River Delta is now looking for faster
economic and infrastructure development and opening to the outside
world, "People's Daily" reports today.
</P>
<P>
The Delta area has 5.17 million people in 12 districts and
counties in the city of Dongying on 18,000 sq km of land, with
about 1.74 million hectares of farmland, as well as oil, copper,
gold and granite reserves.
</P>
<P>
It also has China's second largest oilfield, the Shengli, and
is an important petrochemical, agricultural, animal husbandry, and
fishery center.
</P>
<P>
It has, however, long been economically backward because of
saline soil, various disasters, and unused resources, in sharp
contrast to the prosperity and fast development of the Yangtze
River Delta or the Pearl River Delta in Guangdong Province in the
South.
</P>
<P>
The Delta area's Binzhou Prefecture has had some success with
economic development and opening up to the outside world. One
parcel of land has been turned into high-yield farmland after many
years of development. Seven of its counties have become cotton and
wheat production centers, and other farm and sideline product
centers are being built.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture has 4 pillar industries in textiles, chemicals,
machine-building, and foodstuff, and overseas investors have shown
an interest in it as its infrastructure improves. It has approved
334 overseas-financed ventures and established business ties with
more than 50 countries and regions and exported 3.5 billion yuan
worth of goods in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It has also tried to benefit from the Shenmu-Huanghua project
for transporting coal from northwest China to the northern Chinese
coast for economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0192 </DOCNO>
