<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Murder Suspects of Former Rwandan Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan police have arrested two
Rwandans and one Ugandan who are suspected to be involved in
Saturday's murder of exiled former Rwandan interior minister Seth
Sendashonga and his Kenyan driver in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Police, declining to name the arrested, said Wednesday that
one was a son of a former Rwandese immigration chief, who had
masterminded the killing because of a cash swindle with
Sendashonga while the other two were hired hit-men.
</P>
<P>
The mastermind's father and the murdered, both Hutus, had
previously conspired to steal 54 million U.S. Dollars from the
Rwandan government, said Nairobi Provincial Police Officer Njiru
Kyanda.
</P>
<P>
After they stole the money, it is claimed that Sendashonga
arranged for his accomplice to be murdered in Kigali, the Rwandan
capital, before he went into exile in Kenya in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The organizer tells us he had killed the former minister in
revenge for defrauding his late father, a director of
immigration, of the 54 million U.S. Dollars which they had both
looted while in Rwandan government," said Kyanda.
</P>
<P>
The self-confessed ringleader said he was motivated by
personal revenge, not politics, adding that he was happy about
the successful assassin of Sendashonga, according to the police.
</P>
<P>
The police have also recovered a firearm with seven rounds of
ammunition when detaining the suspected, said Kyanda.
</P>
<P>
However, Sendashonga's widow, who works for the U.N.
Environment Program (UNEP) in Nairobi, denied the police claims
Wednesday and accused the Rwandan Patriotic Front government of a
cover-up in the murder.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Kigali strongly dismissed having any links with the
killing.
</P>
<P>
Police in Nairobi said Wednesday the investigations into the
murder were still under way and all claims would be thoroughly
investigated and the facts verified.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, UNEP Executive Director Klaus Topfer urged the
Kenyan government to take action against surging insecurity in
the capital.
</P>
<P>
Sendashonga, until his death, was a leader of the exiled
opposition Resistance Forces for Democracy in Rwanda. He was
gunned down on the spot during a thunderstorm at a busy junction
in Nairobi on Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He joined the Tutsi-dominated Rwandan Patriotic Front (RPF)
before it seized power in 1994, served as interior minister of
Rwanda in July that year and was sacked in 1995. He then went
into exile in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
He was regarded as a moderate Hutu opposed to the 1994
genocide in which more than 500,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus
were killed.
</P>
<P>
He survived a previous murder attempt on the outskirts of
Nairobi in June 1996 in which his nephew was critically wounded.
</P>
</TEXT>
