<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Discovers 26 Supernovas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Astronomical
Observatory (BAO) attached to the Chinese Academy of Sciences has
discovered 26 supernovas in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The International Astronomical Union has confirmed the BAO's
latest discovery of two new stars in March via Internet.
</P>
<P>
The Xinglong Station of BAO first observed a supernova in
April, 1996 with a home-made astronomical telescope and the
International Astronomical Union confirmed the discovery soon.
</P>
<P>
Since then, BAO discovered another 25 supernovas with the
home-made intelligence telescope, the largest in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
The union has named last June "Xinglong" for one of the
supernovas discovered by the BAO's Xinglong Station in recognition
of its contribution to world astronomical research.
</P>
<P>
China's history books recoded eight nova eruptions.
</P>
<P>
Supernova observation is an important project for astrophysics
and is also an important tool in the research of cosmology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
