<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Railways to Retrench Employees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- About 2,600 employees at the
flagging state-owned Zambia Railways will lose their jobs in a
retrenchment program aimed at saving the company from collapse,
an official from the company has said.
</P>
<P>
The company's Managing Director Rober Crawford Wednesday
confirmed the development as saying that the move is "inevitable"
in the light of the falling freight and passenger services, Times
of Zambia reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The retrenchment program, which will begin before the end of
this year, will affect about half of its 5,200 employees in both
management and unionized scales.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time for the railway company to retrench its
workforce. A total of 700 people were laid off in 1992 whereas
another 2,000 were fired in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The company's management and the union will start negotiating
a retrenchment package immediately, said Crawford. The company
can not maintain a huge workforce when the services are going
down, he added.
</P>
<P>
The freight services has reduced to 1.4 million tons during
the 1997-98 period while five years ago the freight was four
million tons a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
