<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improves Small Valley Areas Along Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- China is making headway in harnessing
small valley areas along the Yangtze River, China's longest, and
some water conservation projects have begun to yield benefits.
</P>
<P>
Pilot projects for comprehensive harnessing were started last
year in 11 small valley areas, involving 7 provinces and
municipalities, according to the Yangtze River Water Resources
Committee under the Ministry of Water Resources.
</P>
<P>
Fengdu County of Sichuan Province, for example, increased
farmers' per-capita farmland to 0.08 hectare and grain output,
672 kilograms, last year, through harnessing the
Duanqiaogou small drainage area.
</P>
<P>
The water and soil conservation area in the Chenshuiwan small
river basin of De'an County, Jiangxi Province, has expanded from
20 ha to more than 33 ha, and the number of fish and pig raising
projects is increasing as a result.
</P>
<P>
By now, 14 provinces and municipalities along the Yangtze River
have opened 33 experimental projects on small valley area
harnessing, and the pilot projects focusing on flood-prevention
are now geared to local development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
