<HEADLINE> Australia to Cooperate With New Indonesian Leader: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Australia would continue to work
with Indonesian President Jusuf Habibie' government, Australian
Prime Minister John Howard said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"My government will cooperate fully with Dr. Habibie's
administration as we have in the past cooperated with the former
President Soeharto's administration," Howard told reporters in
Canberra.
</P>
<P>
"There is a very big challenge ahead for Indonesia. It is
important that international economic confidence be built," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Howard said Australia wanted further political reform in
Indonesia but it was up to the Indonesian people to decide the
pace of that reform.
</P>
<P>
Howard refused to speculate on whether the government would
offer further aid to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think it's appropriate at this stage for me to be
speculating about further initiatives. It's only a couple of weeks
since we announced a 30 million Australian dollar (19 million U.S.
dollar) humanitarian aid package," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government regards Indonesia as the third most
important nation after the United States and Japan to Australia,
and has been helping Indonesia politically and economically in
recent years instead of criticizing its largest neighbor as some
Western nations have done.
</P>
<P>
Also Thursday, Australian opposition leader Kim Beazley called
on the Australian government to take a leading role in the
humanitarian relief effort which would soon be needed in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The likelihood of food shortages was so great that Australia
should start to organize international efforts in the time
remaining before the crisis, the Australian Labor Party leader
said.
</P>
<P>
Beazley made the appeal following the resignation of Indonesian
President Soeharto Thursday morning. 
</P>
