<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Indonesian Crisis May Affect Asia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Asian markets may take a breather
from the Indonesian crisis in the days ahead after President
Soeharto resigned Thursday, but the crisis seems far from over and
could affect Asia's recovery process.
</P>
<P>
In the last few days, financial markets across the region were
battered by violence on the Jakarta streets and confusion in
Indonesia's corridors of power.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen fell to 136.4 against the U.S. dollar Tuesday
and Wednesday, the lowest in seven years, while the Indonesia's
rupiah hit the 12,000 level to the greenback after its recent
recovery. Other currencies and stock markets in the region also
tumbled.
</P>
<P>
Although Asian markets could breathe a sigh of relief after
Soeharto's resignation, the calm in the market might be only
temporary as the situation in that country is still very delicate,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
They said that if the crisis continues to deteriorate, not only
the financial markets but also the whole recovery process in the
region could be jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
At present, the immediate effect of the crisis on the Asian
economic recovery is the possible holdback of investment in the
region because prolonged anarchy in Indonesia would scare away
both foreign and domestic investors.
</P>
<P>
At an international investment conference meeting in Geneva
last week, investors were told to avoid troubled Asia, where
economic recovery could be affected by the outbreak of violence in
Indonesia, India's nuclear tests and other problems.
</P>
<P>
It is quite natural that investors will reassess Asia's
recovery prospects if Indonesia continues on its current path,
said Bill Belchere, economist at Merlin Lynch in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
After being hit severely by the 10-month-old financial crisis,
countries such as South Korea, Thailand, Indonesia and the
Philippines are badly in need of foreign funds to speed up their
economic recovery process. The potential withdrawal of funds will
reopen the region's economic wounds.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the potential reduction in foreign investment,
the deterioration of the Indonesian economy would also impede the
economic recovery in the region.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, whose economy occupies about one fourth of the gross
domestic product of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN), has close economic relations with other countries in the
region, especially with Singapore and Malaysia, both ASEAN
members.
</P>
<P>
During the past week, many foreign and domestic investors and
business executives fled Indonesia, shops and factories were
closed in major cities, and the International Monetary Fund and
the Asian Development Bank withheld bailout loans to the nation.
All these factors have pushed the Indonesian economy to the edge
of collapse.
</P>
<P>
As its trade and economic partners, countries in the region
could be hit by Indonesia's economic conditions, economists said.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Japanese banks are owed 23 billion U.S.
dollars by private Indonesian borrowers, and the delay of
repayment of the debts by Indonesian companies seems disastrous
for Japan's bad debt-burdened banks.
</P>
<P>
Some economists warned that the unrest in Indonesia could spark
a new wave of panic-selling across the region, thus triggering
renewed turmoil in the region's financial markets.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the influx of Indonesian refugees to neighboring
countries will also create security and social problems for these
countries and weaken the confidence of investors in Indonesia's
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Western diplomats here said that the strife in Indonesia is
Singapore's nightmare come to life.
</P>
<P>
Singapore has long been nervous about an influx of Indonesian
boat people across the Straits of Malacca, which is clearly
worrisome.
</P>
<P>
As the Indonesian crisis seems far from over, economists are
still assessing the implications of the crisis for the Asian
economy. But one thing is certain: the long-term effect of the
crisis on the regional economy will be very profound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
