<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jilin Strengthens Environment Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Jilin province,
one of China's heavy industrial bases, has strengthened
international cooperation in environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The province has introduced foreign advanced equipment and
funds conducting monitoring and protection of local environmental
developments.
</P>
<P>
Fu Xing, director of the Jilin Provincial Bureau for
Environmental Protection, said that Jilin has close relations of
cooperation with neighboring countries including the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea(DPRK), the Republic of Korea(ROK),
Japan and Russia in environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
According to Fu, the Changbai Mountains in the eastern part of
the province have rich forest and biological resources and feed a
number of rivers including the Tumen River, Songhua River and the
Yalu River.
</P>
<P>
Fu said that Jilin Province and the DPRK signed an agreement to
harness the Tumen River in 1982, according to which the two sides
work to reduce pollutants discharged into the river and will
exchange related information and jointly conduct monitoring.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Development Program has conducted research and
evaluation of the water quality of the Tumen River valley, and a
sewage treatment plant has been built in Huichun city, a
state-level development zone, to reduce pollution.
</P>
<P>
Japan has also joined in to help harness the Tumen River, which
empties in the Sea of Japan.
</P>
<P>
Fu said that Jilin has obtained an investment of 100 million US
dollars from the Japanese side to establish three sewage treatment
plants in the Tumen River valley. The three plants have an annual
handling capacity of 800,000 tons and are expected to help reduce
pollutants by 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the two sides have also cooperated in investigating
and monitoring the ecological environment in the Changbai
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
A regular forum on environmental protection has also been held
among the four nations of China, Japan, the ROK and Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Practice of Classifying New Bank Loans Introduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China, the
central bank, has selected the economic power house of Guangdong
province to experiment with classifying new loans in a bid to
improve the management on credit loans.
</P>
<P>
Beginning this month, banks in Guangdong, adjacent to Hong
Kong, has already begun with with the "five grade" classification,
which is said to comply with the international practice. And in
August, the banks nationwide will have to introduce the practice.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, which emphasizes risk management, loans will
be classified into five categories, namely, "the standard, special
mention, substandard, doubtful and loss." This is different from
the previously-used loan classification that was focused on
management according to loan terms.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, governor of the central bank, told a bank
meeting held in Guangzhou recently that the new system is designed
to better reflect the risk, real value, and quality of bank loans.
</P>
<P>
Lu Ruihua, Guangdong's provincial governor, said that selecting
his province to experiment with the new system reflects the
support of the central government and the concern of the
province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
