<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Reiterates Constructive Engagement with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States government
Wednesday reiterated its adherence to the constructive engagement
policy toward China as the White House is preparing President
Bill Clinton's state visit to China next month.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters on the visit, spokesman Michael McCurry
said, "We're going there despite all the differences we have with
the People's Republic to try to work constructively to improve
this relationship, which is so important to billions -- literally
billions -- of people."
</P>
<P>
He rejected calls by some U.S. legislators for Clinton to
eschew a formal welcome normally reserved for heads of state when
he starts his trip on June 25.
</P>
<P>
"To ask that we not be received in a manner in which you would
normally be received at a state visit would do some violence to
the idea that we are trying to work in a cooperative way to
improve this relationship," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
"It would be as if someone visiting here said, 'Well, we don't
really want to be greeted on the South Lawn of the White House
even though that's where people are greeted when they arrive for
state visit,'" he said.
</P>
<P>
McCurry also said that the U.S. easing on its export of
satellite technology had no connection with campaign fund-raising
and denied that allowing U.S. companies to launch their satellites
on Chinese rockets damaged U.S. security.
</P>
<P>
He criticized House Speaker Newt Gingrich for planning to set
up a special panel to investigate Sino-U.S. satellite launching
contacts.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives Wednesday approved four
amendments to the fiscal 1999 Defense Department spending bill
aiming to restrict U.S. export of sensitive satellite and missile
technology to China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
