<HEADLINE> Clinton Welcomes Suharto's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton Wednesday
welcomed Indonesian President Suharto's decision to step down,
calling the move a "peaceful process" that would lead to a
democratic transition for Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome President Suharto's decision, which provides an
opportunity to begin a process leading to a real democratic
transition for Indonesia -- an opportunity for the Indonesian
people to come together and build a stable democracy for the
future," Clinton said in a statement read by a White House
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"We urge Indonesia's leaders to move forward promptly with a
peaceful process that enjoys broad public support," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the United States stood ready to support Indonesia
as it moved toward creation of a stable democracy.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright urged
Suharto to perform a "historic act of statesmanship" and open the
way for democracy.
</P>
<P>
Albright's statement, issued about 10 hours before Suharto
decided to resign, was seen here as an appeal ouched in diplomatic
code asking him to step down.
</P>
<P>
"Now he has the opportunity for a historic act of
statesmanship, one that will preserve his legacy as a man who not
only led his country but who provided for his democratic
transition," Albright said in a speech at the U.S. Coast Guard
Academy in New London, Connecticut. 
</P>
</TEXT>
