<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launches Qinghai-Tibet Plateau Meterological Experiment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- China has launched the second
meterological experiment on the Qinghai-Tibet plateau, according
to sources from the Tibet Autonomous Regional Meterological Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that on-the-spot experiments are being carried
out from May 10 to August 10, in addition to theoretical
studies. The aim of the experiments is to study the influence of
global climate changes and disastrous climates in China caused by
air flows from the Qinghai-Tibet plateau.
</P>
<P>
Related experiments cover land and high-altitude meterological
monitoring, atmospheric boundary layer, atmospheric ozone and
solar radiation.
</P>
<P>
China launched its first such experiment in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, three other meterological experiments including
experiments on South China Sea monsoon, rainstorms in south China
and analysis of energy and water cycling in the Huaihe River
valley are going on smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The experiments are carried out by scientific and technological
workers from China and a dozen other countries including the
United States, Japan, Australia and the Republic of Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Uses Caissons to Build Oil Platforms in Bohai Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- China has started to sink caissons
to build offshore oil platforms at the Jinzhou 9-3 Oilfield in the
Bohai Bay, according to Lin Shaodong, president of the China
Offshore Oil Bohai Corporation, as a new way of doing the
construction work.
</P>
<P>
Jinzhou 9-3 Oilfield is in icy waters about 20 km from the city
of Jinzhou in Liaoning Province and has more than 30 million tons
of proven reserves.
</P>
<P>
Lin says that conventional methods of construction would be
very costly and make it difficult to recover the investment. So,
after eight years of studies, Chinese petroleum geologists decided
to use the steel boxes for efficiency and safety.
</P>
<P>
At present, 13.8-m-high containers that are 38 m. in diameter
are in place.
</P>
<P>
Jinzhou Oilfield is designed to have 27 oil wells, 26 water
injecting wells, and one natural gas well, and an annual oil
drilling capacity of one million tons. The oilfield will go into
production in 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
