<HEADLINE> Kuwait Urged to Open Economy to Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti government has been
urged to to open its economy to foreign investors by removing
bureaucratic hurdles and simplifying investment regulations, the
English-language Kuwait Times reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by foreign diplomats here, especially
U.S. ambassador James Larocco.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar on "Kuwait's economic security in the 21st
century" Wednesday, Larocco expressed the hope that investment in
Kuwait will grow and opportunities for investment will improve in
the days to come.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that new policies need to be evolved to provide
better investment climate to attract investors.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait should aggressively seek foreign investment through
clear guidelines, rules, and incentives that will attract
technology transfer, create employment, and provide managerial and
technical know-how young Kuwaitis are looking for, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also voiced concern about Kuwait's high tax rate on foreign
investors, which has reached a staggering 55 percent on income.
This is the one of the reasons why there is so little foreign
investment in Kuwait, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
