<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ship Conducting Scientific Exploration in Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese ship has been sent to the
northeastern Pacific Ocean for scientific studies.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists will study the topographical, chemical,
biological, and geological features of the region, and mining and
metallurgical possibilities there.
</P>
<P>
The ship, "Ocean No. 1," is carrying modern equipment like a
special transponder and robots capable of working at a depth of
6,000 m.
</P>
<P>
China has a 150,000-sq.km. marine mining region in the
northeastern Pacific, which was approved by the United Nation in
1991. But, China will relinquish control over 50 percent of the
region before March 1999, according to UN regulations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese conducted five explorations in the region during the
1990-1995 period and will make another four explorations in the
next few years to set the boundaries of the 75,000 sq.km. region
it wants to keep for mining in the next century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
