<HEADLINE> Citibank Buys Shares of Chinese Air Conditioner Maker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Citibank of the United States
has acquired 40 percent of the stake of a leading Chinese
air-conditioner maker with an investment term of 30 years.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Guoduan, Chairman and General Manager of the
Guangdong Kelong Air-conditioner Co. Ltd., which is listed in Hong
Kong, Citibank has spent 187 million yuan (22.53 million US
dollars) for the Kelong stake, adding that the bank will not take
over the management of the company.
</P>
<P>
Kelong's tangible assets are valued at 300 million yuan and
intangible assests at 168 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The company issued H shares in the Hong Kong bourse in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A Kelong spokesman said the company believes that the
participation of Citibank can improve the capital structure of the
company and expand the company's market recognition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cable TV Business Projected to Grow Rapidly In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- China expects to have 100 million
cable TV customers by the year 2000, according to industry sources.
</P>
<P>
Government departments estimate that 70 million people have
cable TV in China, most of whom are families, and that the number
is growing 10 percent annually, and that 17 percent of the
households have it. But, only 9 percent of Chinese households have
telephones and only 1.2 percent have computers.
</P>
<P>
The government has approved over 1,200 cable TV companies,
which have cable networks in over 70 percent of the cities and
counties.
</P>
<P>
The government is using foreign funds to put together a
national network, and the next step is to connect the national hub
to provincial hubs and then to county hubs.
</P>
<P>
Fred Yang, of Philips Broadband Networks China, says that both
foreign and Chinese companies are concentrating on tapping the
wide-band communication capacity of China's network, which
will be used both for entertainment and for telephone, data, and
electronic-business services.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, Shenzhen, and Dalian already have interactive cable
TV networks that combine broadcast, telecommunications, and
internet functions.
</P>
<P>
A Shanghai representative of the U.S.'s Scientific Atlanta says
that the business is growing so fast in China that it is difficult
to tell what will happen in several years, and that it is an
exciting business.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
