<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Records Most Serious Sea Disasters in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- China recorded the most serious sea
disasters last year since the founding of new China in 1949,
sources from the National Bureau of Oceanography said here today.
</P>
<P>
Ye Renmiao, director of the forecasting department of the
bureau, said that last year's windstorms, typhoons, oceanic ice
and abnormal marine phenomena killed over 200 people and caused an
economic loss of over 30 billion yuan (3.5 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that last year, China's coastal areas were hit by
four typhoons, all in August.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon "No. 11" or "Typhoon Winnie", in particular, hit
Shanghai and Tianjin municipalities, and the provinces of
Zhejiang, Fujian, Jiangsu, Shandong, Hebei and Liaoning, causing a
record economic loss of over 26 billion yuan (some 3 billion US
dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Bureau of Oceanography, the "Typhoon
Winnie" destroyed more than 770 kilometers of coastal embankments
and damaged over 1,000 vessels.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that heavy land pollution also polluted the country's
offshore areas.
</P>
<P>
He said, in 1997, red tides hit China's offshore areas eight
times, and a rare red tide of blue green alga hit Xiamen of Fujian
province and Guangrao of Guangdong province last October and
November respectively.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, deterioration of the water quality and abnormal
marine phenomena caused the massive death of scallops off north
China's vast sea waters. The National Bureau of Oceanography asked
coastal provinces and cities to pay close attention to reports on
marine developments and enhance disaster relief efforts, to reduce
loss as far as possible.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
