<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Culture, Sports Meeting Opens in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The seventh session for SADC
officials of culture, information and sports opened here
Wednesday with emphasis on the need for comprehensive regional
policies and harmonized program for the sectors.
</P>
<P>
The meeting attended by permanent secretaries and ministers of
culture, information and sports of the SADC (Southern African
Development Community) member states, will review decisions made
at a similar meeting in May last year, and cover the issue of
pirating.
</P>
<P>
Participants have been tasked to come up with ways of curbing
pirating in the regional states.
</P>
<P>
They will review achievements made in culture theater within
the region and prepare for the Dance Festival to be held in
Mauritius next year.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also evaluate the extent to which various
SADC media institutions have been able to exchange information
and portray achievements made by member states.
</P>
<P>
A report on sporting people with disabilities will also be
discussed in an effort to come up with ways of improving their
sporting activities and facilities.
</P>
<P>
Opening the meeting, Zimbabwean Minister of Education, Sports
and Culture Gabriel Machinga said that resolutions to be made at
the meeting should form the basis for making the region's
culture, information and sports sector into an action oriented
body.
</P>
<P>
He stressed culture, information and sports could improve the
quality of life for the regional people and develop their
economies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
