<HEADLINE> Tame Tigers In China Being Encouraged To Find Mate In Wild </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese animal keepers are trying to
make conditions favorable enough to get tame tigers to mate with
tigers in the wild to increase the number of South China Tigers,
which are on the verge of extinction.
</P>
<P>
A project has been started in Fujian Province, where Meihua
Mountains are known as the home of the South China Tiger and a few
of the animals can still be found there.
</P>
<P>
Some tigers from zoos will be sent to a certain part of the
mountains to attract the animals living in the wild, according to
an official in the city of Longyan, which has spent 1.5 million
yuan on the project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
