<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legal Status of Kazakhstan New Capital Established </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev signed a decree Wednesday, establishing the legal
status of Astana as the capital of Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
According to the decree, Astana will be the country's political
and executive center, where the presidency, legislature,
administration, the supreme court and the supreme procurate are
stationed, reported the Kazakhstan Telegraph Agency.
</P>
<P>
The decree stipulates that Astana's mayor will be nominated by
the prime minister and appointed by the president while its
running will be in the charge of a local executive organ under the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
The decree allows implementation of special economic policies
in the new capital or its surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Nazarbayev announced at a government-parliament
joint meeting in Akmola that the city would become the nation's
"permanent capital" on December 10, 1997.
</P>
<P>
On May 6, 1998, he signed a document, changing Akmola, meaning
"white tomb" in Kazakh, to Astana, meaning "capital."
</P>
<P>
A grand official ceremony will be held on June 10 in the new
capital, 1,300 kilometers north of here with an area of 200 square
kilometers and a population of 300,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
