<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Indonesian Former President Soeharto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jakarta, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
resigned Thursday morning. Following is his profile.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was born in a farmer family in the densely-populated
Central Java on June 8, 1921. His father was a village staff in
charge of water distribution service.
</P>
<P>
He only received formal education at a junior high school, but
later with the military training and education, he won his laurels
and obtained the highest military and civilian positions.
</P>
<P>
Starting as a non-commissioned officer in the Dutch colonial
army and a member of the Indonesian militia during the Japanese
occupation, Soeharto was promoted to the country's military
leadership when he distinguished himself during the fight for
independence in the second half of the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was regimental commander, brigadier general and major
general from 1945 to 1962. From 1970 to 1965, he worked as deputy
chief of army staff and then as chief of army staff between 1965
and 1968.
</P>
<P>
He became acting president in 1967 to replace Indonesia's
founding president Soekarno. Then he became president in 1968. He
has since run unopposed and elected by acclamation for six times.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) in March 1998
elected 76-year-old President Soeharto to his seventh five-year
term of office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
