<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dust Pollution Harms Million Bangkok Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Dust pollution has harmed more than
a million Bangkok residents, resulting in more than 88 billion
baht (2.3 billion U.S. dollars) being spent on their medical
treatment, according to a study of the Pollution Control
Department (PCD).
</P>
<P>
Even though the current level of dust content in Bangkok was 30
percent lower than last year, it was still above the safety
standard, the Nation newspaper Thursday quoted the study as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The study stressed that health problems are usually caused by
small particulate matters with diameter of less than 10 microns
and capable of being inhaled into the lung, and whose average
level is 13 percent higher than the World Health Organization
standard of 0.51 micrograms per cubic meter.
</P>
<P>
The study said the main sources of dust pollution in Bangkok
are dust from the roads and emissions from vehicles and factories.
</P>
<P>
The study was funded by the World Bank, and aimed at seeking
proper measures to draw a master plan for dust pollution
management.
</P>
<P>
Sirithan Pairojboriboon, PCD's director general, was quoted by
the Nation as saying that the study had suggested five measures,
including replacing the two-wheelers with four-wheelers; enforcing
diesel trucks to use benzene or natural gas instead of diesel;
strictly controlling emissions from diesel trucks; cleaning the
roads in the metropolis; and changing the fuel used by power
plants and factories from crude oil to natural gas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
