<HEADLINE> Thailand Eyes to Be Regional Food Production Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Food-Processing Industry Club
of the Federation of Thai Industries has set a five-year master
plan aimed at transforming Thailand into a regional food
production center by 2003.
</P>
<P>
According to a report Thursday, the plan launched this year
will require local manufacturers to improve raw material quality,
production technology and marketing to ensure sustainable export
growth with a view to eventually making Thailand a world-class
food production center.
</P>
<P>
Club Chairman Surapon Vongadhanaroj was quoted as saying that
to become a food center, Thailand would have to be able to cope
with competition from world-class manufacturers such as Nestles
and Unilever, which are recognized by consumers the world over for
their marketing, brand names and product quality.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has many advantages attractive to manufacturers, such
as local raw materials, a skilled workforce, experience in the
food industry and export credibility. The problem facing the
manufacturers is how to translate these advantages into increased
productivity.
</P>
<P>
Food exports generated 226.7 billion baht (5.9 billion U.S.
dollars) last year, up 20.2 percent compared with 1996, and
accounting for 12.5 percent of the country's total exports. The
food industry's total registered capital is around 11.93 billion
baht (313 million dollars) with more than 2,500 factories
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Major export products are fishery products, livestock, rice,
vegetables and fruits, and the main markets are Japan, other ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) countries and the
European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
