<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment Expected to Rise in Thailand: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Unemployment in Thailand topped the
government's estimates early this year and is expected to rise
higher after the middle of the year when new graduates are due to
enter the job market, the Nation newspaper Thursday quoted a
national statistics office survey as saying.
</P>
<P>
To make matter worse, severe drought triggered by the El Nino
weather phenomenon has prevented the agricultural sector from
absorbing the unemployed who have been returning to their rural
homes to work on farms, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Labor Ministry's forecast, the number of
jobless people may reach 2 million by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
But the National Statistics Office discovered that the number
is much higher than the ministry expected.
</P>
<P>
The survey said, at the end of February the unemployment rate
reached 4.7 percent, about 2.8 million, including the 1.3
seasonally unemployed.
</P>
<P>
The rate is higher than the unemployment standard of 3 percent
of population set by the International Labor Organization.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry reported earlier that more than 200,000
laid-off workers have returned to their home towns in rural areas
to work on farms. But the survey found that those people are still
jobless because the agricultural sector has been hit hard by
drought.
</P>
<P>
The statistics office also expected the jobless number to
increase with additional entrants of the 500,000 graduated
students in middle of the year.
</P>
<P>
However, the labor ministry refused to accept the number of the
survey, saying the 1.3 million seasonally unemployed was an
exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's Permanent Secretary Phan Chantarapan said staff
had been ordered to check the accuracy of the number.
</P>
<P>
He also vowed to stick to the solution to the mass national
unemployment according to the government plan.
</P>
<P>
The government last week allocated an urgent budget of about 9
billion baht (230.8 million U.S. dollars) for job creation through
short-term investment projects by government units as a part of
the social safety net program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
