<HEADLINE> Water Supply Crisis in Dhaka Turns Critical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The water shortage situation in the
capital city of Dhaka this summer has turned critical with no
signs of improvement, an English daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Residents in different parts of the city had been asking the
municipal government to take measures to ensure the required
supply of water, The Financial Express said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Dhaka Water and Sewerage Authority can only
meet about 64 percent of the demand for water supply in the city,
supplying around 900 million liters per day against the demand of
more than 1.4 billion liters.
</P>
<P>
People in many areas of the city with a population of more than
9 million have been compelled to go without water for many days.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the water and sewerage authority said the main
reasons for the supply crisis included load-shedding, low voltage
and unplanned growth of the city, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a system loss of around 45 percent had also made the
situation worse, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Dhaka municipal government is expediting the implementation
of some water projects and plans to take effective measures to
reduce system losses to ensure the water supply of the city, they
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
