<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Grants One Day Amnesty to Army Deserters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
announced a one day amnesty for army deserters next Sunday from
8:00 a.m. to midnight. Earlier the government declared a five-day
amnesty from May 5 to 10 which brought in a partial response,
police sources here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 15,000 deserters 5,892 reported back for duty and
subsequently 1,768 were arrested by the police upto now.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the one day amnesty is in response
to a strong appeal made by various public representative
requesting the government to grant relief for deserters to return
for duty without being arrested.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the last and final amnesty announced by
government which ended on May 10 saw 5,892 deserters returning for
duty.
</P>
<P>
The operation to arrest absconding deserters which began with
the ending of the amnesty made it possible to round up 1,768
deserters.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly the number of deserters surrendered and arrested is
7,660, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan government forces engaged in a 15-year war with the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam rebels who are fighting for a
separate state, are faced with a severe manpower problem, Army
Commander Rohan Daluwatte confessed last week.
</P>
<P>
He added that they had launched a major recruitment drive
islandwide and if it fails they would be compelled to conscript
youth between 18 and 30 years of age. 
</P>
