<HEADLINE> Northeastern Chinese Company Issuing B-Shares On Shanghai Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Stock of the Jinzhou Port (Group)
Co. Ltd. of China's Liaoning Province is now being traded on the
Shanghai Stock Exchange, as of May 19.
</P>
<P>
China's two stock exchanges, in Shanghai and Shenzhen, trade
two major kinds of stocks, A-shares for domestic investors and
B-shares for overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
The group company issued 100 million B-shares with a face value
of one yuan, which sold for 0.21 U.S. dollars. The proceeds from the
issue will be used for a bulk cargo berth and expansion of a
goods storage area, a company executive says.
</P>
<P>
The company's B-shares are the only new ones to be added to the
Shanghai exchange this year and are the only B-shares of a port
facility. The Jinzhou Port Group was established on December 30,
1992 and was the first port to issue shares in China.
</P>
<P>
The volume of cargo handled there has been increasing 41
percent annually since 1993. Last year, it handled more than five
million tons of cargo.
</P>
<P>
The port now has six berths for ships of 10,000 dwt and has
shipping service to all Chinese coastal ports and to a dozen
countries and regions.  
</P>
