<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Van Goghs, One Cezanne Stolen from Rome Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Two masterpieces by Vincent van Gogh
and a third by Paul Cezanne were stolen from Italy's National
Gallery of Modern Art Tuesday night, Italian Culture Minister
Walter Veltroni said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Veltroni said the police hypothesized that the robbery occurred
at 10 p.m. local time when three masked and armed men entered the
museum and walked off with the three masterpieces in their frames.
</P>
<P>
Van Gogh's "The Gardener," which depicts a man in a
broad-brimmed hat, dates back to 1889, while "L'Arlesienne," a
portrait of one of van Gogh's friends, was painted one year
later. This portrait was among the master's favorites.
</P>
<P>
Cezanne's unfinished landscape "Le Cabanon de Jourdan", was
painted in 1906, the year of his death.
</P>
<P>
Some Italian art experts estimated the total worth of the
paintings at about 30 million U.S. dollars, but others insisted
the works, especially for historical value, could not carry a
price-tag.
</P>
<P>
Robbery of art works has become more and more frequent in Italy
in recent years. Although the Italian government spent some 570
million dollars per year on security against art theft, a total of
2,653 such cases were registered in 1994-97. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
