<HEADLINE> hke - World Bank President Urges Russia to Reassure Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank president Wednesday
urged the Russian government to take a series of emergency
measures to reassure panicked investors.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Moscow international relations institute, James
Wolfensohn said Russia was too dependent on short-term bonds,
making the current economy very vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn said it is impossible to solve the development issue
by way of foreign loans. He urged the country to cut its budget
deficit and increase its public revenue.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Interfax news agency, the president
said Russia had made some improvement in terms of using World Bank
social development loans.
</P>
<P>
However, Russia was able to do much better and the government
needed to further cooperate with the World Bank, Wolfensohn added.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Wolfensohn met with Russian Deputy Prime
Ministers Viktor Khristenko and Oleg Sysuyev and discussed health
and education projects. He also talked with Finance Minister
Mikhail Zadornov.
</P>
<P>
The Russian economy edged up 0.4 percent last year after
shrinking every previous year in the 1990s. The government has
forecast 2 percent growth this year, but recent problems have
reduced those prospects.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn, who arrived on Tuesday evening, is due to meet with
President Boris Yeltsin and Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
Russia has received some 10 billion U.S. dollars from the World
Bank. A further three billion dollars has been promised for this
year. 
</P>
