<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 14 Killed in Cyclone in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- At least 14 people were killed and
more than 100 injured in a cyclone that hit Bangladesh's coastal
districts of Cox's Bazar and Chittagong Wednesday, sources of the
government's Central Relief Control Room said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Besides, about 100 fishermen were missing in the cyclone with a
maximum wind speed of 150 kilometers an hour, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Some 10,000 houses were razed, a lot of trees and electric
poles uprooted, and crops on 10,000 acres of land inundated
following the cyclone. Tidal surges caused by the cyclone also
washed away 50,000 tons of salt, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Authorities concerned declared Wednesday Chittagong
International Airport unfit for operation for 24 hours because of
the silt brought by the tidal surge arising from the cyclone.
</P>
<P>
Cyclone-hit people had been evacuated to different shelters,
and members of the armed forces and the local administration had
distributed dry food to them, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Red Crescent Society had taken measures to ascertain
the losses caused by the cyclone, and instructed its volunteers in
the coastal districts to play an effective role in rescue
operations in the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
Preparation beforehand had helped reduce the damage of the
cyclone, according to State Minister for Manpower M. A. Mannan who
visited the affected areas Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
