<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia's New Cabinet Emerges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Momir Bulatovic has been
accredited as prime minister of the Government of the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY) by separate votes in the two federal
assembly (parliament) chambers.
</P>
<P>
Tanjug news agency said Wednesday that 95 out of the 138
members of the Chamber of Citizens and 25 of the Chamber of
Republics' 40 delegates voted for Bulatovic's nomination.
</P>
<P>
Bulatovic gave a briefing of his administrative program and
submitted the list of his cabinet members to the joint session of
the two chambers before the legislative votes.
</P>
<P>
He told the houses the new government will work for a
Yugoslavia built on the sound base of social justice and which
deals with internal affairs through democratic means.
</P>
<P>
He looked forward to Yugoslavia's integration into the world
community as early as possible and on conditions of equality and
respect for the dignity of the people and the nation.
</P>
<P>
Bulatovic promised the establishment of an open and
market-oriented economy, with the aim of raising the living
standards of the people and promoting social stability.
</P>
<P>
Three new faces appear in the cabinet beside Bulatovic.
</P>
<P>
Danilo Vuksanovic replaced Vojin Djukanovic as deputy prime
minister. The other four deputy prime ministers retain their posts.
</P>
<P>
Former Finance Minister Bozidar Gazivoda and Labor Minister
Dusko Lalicevic were replaced respectively by Dragisa Pesic,
previously chairman of the federal budgetary council of the
Chamber of Citizens, and Miodrag Kovac, a delegate from Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
The other 14 portfolios remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Bulatovic, born in 1956, is an ethnic Montenegrin. He was
president of the Republic of Montenegro between 1993 and January
1998.
</P>
<P>
He was chairman of the Democratic Party of Socialists from 1990
to March 1998, and took the post of chairman of the Socialist
People's Party in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
