<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Slashes Banks' Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
has agreed to slash banks' reserve requirement on deposits to help
bring down interest rates, the Philippine newspaper Malaya
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Monetary Board, the highest decision-making body of the
central bank, agreed Tuesday to cut banks' statutory reserve
requirement from 10 to 8 percent, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
But banks' liquidity reserves, which should be used to buy
government equities, were retained at 7 percent, and thus, the
total reserve requirement will be 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
As a sweetener for banks, the board also increased from 25
percent to 40 percent the proportion of statutory reserves the
central bank will pay interest in.
</P>
<P>
The new reserve requirements will be in place by May 29.
</P>
<P>
The central bank expects banks to pass on to their clients the
cheaper cost of funds by keeping lending spreads from 1.5 percent
to 6 percent over the benchmark Treasury Bill rate.
</P>
<P>
This means that if the Treasury Bill rate is 14 percent, the
highest rate banks can charge clients is 20 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
