<HEADLINE> Southwestern Chinese Region Spending On Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region will spend 170 billion yuan during the 1998-2000
period on 220 key infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
A government official says that, since 1992, Guangxi's economy
has had an average annual GDP growth of 16.2 percent. To keep this
up, Guangxi will increase spending on infrastructure like water
control, transportation, and hydro-electric power stations.
</P>
<P>
About a billion yuan will be spent this year on 30 medium-sized
and large reservoirs and the first phase of a shelter-belt project
along the Pearl River.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi will also spend 6.75 billion yuan on highway, waterway
and railway construction, berths at Fangcheng port, and
expansion of the Beihai Airport.
</P>
<P>
The region will also invest 7.1 billion yuan in hydro-electric
power and thermal-power stations, 3.9 billion yuan on posts and
telecommunications, and 8 billion yuan on technology improvements.
</P>
<P>
The official also says that Guangxi will do preparatory work on
three large infrastructure projects this year like the first phase
of the Baise water conservation project, costing 6.56 billion
yuan, the Longtan hydro-electric power station, at 37.6 billion
yuan, with a total generating capacity of 4.2 million kw, and the
Guangxi section of the Luoyang-Zhanjiang railway, at a cost of 7
billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
