<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Privatize All Small Commercial Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shanghai municipality
plans to privatize all of its state small commercial firms within
three years, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Shanghai Municipal Commerce Commission
indicated that 179 such businesses in the municipality have
already been privatized, paving the way for across-the-board
privatization of small firms.
</P>
<P>
The commission categorizes small enterprises as those with net
assets below 10 million yuan (1.2 million US dollars). The
majority are losing money or barely making a profit.
</P>
<P>
The commission convened a meeting recently to showcase several
enterprises in Huangpu, Luwan and Hongkou districts that have
successfully changed from State to private ownership.
</P>
<P>
With regard to large- and medium-sized enterprises, the
commission plans to restructure large and medium-sized enterprises
to turn them into shareholding companies in which the State owns
the controlling stakes. This will allow the company managers to be
freed from government administration so that they will be more
responsive to the market.
</P>
<P>
Other provinces and regions in China are also adopting similar
measures to sell their small State-owned enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
