<HEADLINE> Costa Rican President Supports US Joint Patrol Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican President Miguel Angel
Rodriguez on Wednesday expressed his support for a joint
anti-drugs patrol with the United States in the waters of the
Pacific and the Atlantic Oceans.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez made the statement when meeting the U.S. Ambassador
to Costa Rica, Thomas Dodd. The United States is pressuring
Caribbean and Central American countries to accept the presence of
navy cruisers in their waters so as to stop drug trafficking in
the region.
</P>
<P>
However, not everyone among Costa Rica's leadership is willing
to accept the joint patrol proposal. The attorney general has
warned the proposal violates the Costa Rican constitution.
</P>
<P>
"We have to defend ourselves from drugs and maintain our
sovereignty. We must find a balance," Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
"I share in this idea of patrolling our seas adequately and at
the least possible cost," the president said, adding that the
proposal could also improve the relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
The relationship was strained when Washington dispatched a
minor official to head a U.S. delegation for the inauguration of
Costa Rica's new president on May 8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
