<HEADLINE> China's E-Business Doing Well (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- China's electronic-business market
is expanding rapidly, with a large number of cyberspace commercial
networks springing up in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Vice-President of the Chinese Academy of Engineering Zhu
Gaofeng became one of the first persons in China to purchase a
CD-ROM from internet earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
He said that local E-business services are "convenient and
efficient."
</P>
<P>
Last week, he visited an on-line CD shop sponsored by the
Beijing-based Guoxin Technology Company on internet. He placed an
order through a personal computer and received the CD-ROM in a week.
</P>
<P>
China now has on-line book stores, booking offices, travel
agents, shopping malls and banks.
</P>
<P>
In early April, the National Commodity Trading Center put into
operation a nationwide E-business network that can be accessed
through Internet. So far, millions of yuan worth of contract have
been signed and payment made through the on-line system.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that Chinese people have come to realize the
advantages of E-business. He said that people have yet to break
the traditional forms of trading and do business via Internet.
</P>
<P>
In mid-April, China's first on-line stock brokerage system went
into operation in Shanghai, enabling investors elsewhere to deal
in via Internet stocks on the country's two stock exchanges in
Shanghai and Shenzhen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
