<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's E-Business Doing Well (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Bank of China has established the country's first standard
electronic banking network. Customers around the country and in
the world can have access to their bank accounts and make
deals through computers linked with the bank's branches or
at ATM machines in China.
</P>
<P>
An executive officer of the Guoxin Technology Company said that
China's on-line service companies enjoy a competitive edge over
their foreign counterparts in E-business applications in the
country.
</P>
<P>
He said that many international IT giants have just put forward
theoretical solutions to E-business in China while local on-line
service providers have built networks that support the flow of
information, funds and goods.
</P>
<P>
Small- and medium-sized enterprises emerge as the largest group
of beneficiaries of the rapidly expanding E-business in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Xu Minghua, a farmer in east China's Jiangsu Province, has been
marketing farm products of his village via Internet since 1997. He
found overseas buyers for 80 percent of the village's
produces. Earlier this year, he received an order from the United
States for 200,000 yuan worth of loofah.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of the Information Industry Lu Xinkui said that
E-business is one of the priorities that the Chinese government
will give in expanding the national IT industry.
</P>
<P>
Now China has established the framework of several nation-wide
electronic data networks, including the telecommunications
network, the computer-supported national economic information
network, cable TV network and electronic networks for many
specific industries.
</P>
<P>
Local IT experts pointed out that China has yet to establish a
sound market order in the process of promoting E-business.
</P>
<P>
China should formulate laws and regulations on E-business and a
universal credit evaluating system, they noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
