<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multilateral Trading Hailed at WTO Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Members of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) agree that the multilateral trading system has
played a significant role in reducing tariffs, promoting world
trade and lifting living standards since the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade (GATT) went into force 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The WTO director-general, Renato Ruggiero, made the remarks at
a press conference here Wednesday at the end of the organization's
three-day ministerial conference, the second since it replaced the
GATT in 1996.
</P>
<P>
WTO statistics show global merchandise exports grew by 6.8
percent per year on an annual average from 1948 to 1997, and
output by 3.8 percent. In 1997, global trade totalled 6.5 trillion
U.S. dollars, 14 times more than that of 1950.
</P>
<P>
At the closing session, WTO members unanimously approved a
proposal by the United States to hold the third ministerial
conference in the U.S. in the fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The exact date and the venue are yet to be decided by the WTO
General Council.
</P>
<P>
Also by consensus, the organization adopted another
U.S. proposal on global electronic commerce. It suggested that no
customs duties be imposed on electronic transmissions.
</P>
<P>
The proposal calls for a comprehensive work program to be drawn
up at the next special session of the general council to examine
all trade-related issues on global electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
It especially urges the council to "take into account the
economic, financial, and development needs of the developing
countries" in the work program.
</P>
<P>
"Globalization is a reality," Ruggiero said. Different members
had different ways to manage it.
</P>
<P>
He noted with delight that these proposals were adopted by
consensus despite differences between the members.
</P>
<P>
The WTO director general reaffirmed his support for China's
entry into the WTO. He called on the two sides in the negotiations
to make joint efforts for an early conclusion.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Chinese delegation to the conference, Long Yongtu,
said that as the multilateral trading system turned 50, the WTO
must face two realities -- the political reality that more than
100 members out of a total of 132 were from the developing world,
and the economic reality that world trade was more and more
integrated.
</P>
<P>
This, he said, constituted a big challenge to the WTO as to how
to ensure that all its members, big or small, rich or poor, shared
the benefits of economic globalization on a justified basis in the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
China hoped that by participating in the multilateral trading
system, it would be able to work with the WTO and make its own
contributions to the establishment of a fair and reasonable world
economic order in the new century, said Long. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts and figures About Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Following are facts and figures
about Indonesia:
</P>
<P>
Geography -- Indonesia, the largest archipelago nation in the
world, consists of a group of about 17,500 islands, lying between
the mainland of Southeast Asia and Australia. The islands stretch
from the Malay peninsula to New Guinea. It has an area of 1.9
million sq. kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Population -- With a population of 202 million by the end of
December 1997, Indonesia is the fourth most populous nation in the
world after China, India, and the United States. It is home to
more than 300 ethnic groups and scores of languages and dialects.
The country includes an urban middle class and tribes barely out
of the stone age.
</P>
<P>
Official language -- Bahasa Indonesia, based on the Malay
language indigenous to the region, is the unifying language among
more than 200 distinct regional languages.
</P>
<P>
Capital -- Jakarta with a population of more than nine million.
</P>
<P>
Religion -- About 88 percent of the 202 million inhabitants say
they are followers of the Sunni branch of Islam, making it the
world's largest Muslim country. Roughly 10 percent are Christians
and approximately two percent Hindu and Buddhists.
</P>
<P>
Economy -- Sustained economic growth pushed per capita gross
domestic product from 60 U.S. dollars in the late 1960s to 1,089
U.S. dollars in 1997. The economy boomed in the 1970s with oil and
natural gas exports and diversified in the 1980s to create a
wide-ranging manufacturing base. However, the country's economy
has been hit badly since July last year by the financial crisis
with the rupiah's value having dropped by about 80 percent and
many economic activities being scaled down.
</P>
<P>
Armed Forces -- 500,000 including the police forces.
</P>
<P>
Government -- Indonesia declared independence from the
Netherlands and Japan on August 17, 1945. The government is
structured as a unitary republic; the 1945 constitution vests the
highest authority in the People's Consultative Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
