<HEADLINE> Growth In Central Chinese Information Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province, an
underdeveloped area, had 65.6 percent growth in its information
technology industry in 1997, with an output value of 3.4 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Hunan is second only to Guangdong, the country's most
successful province in growth in that industry, according to the
Provincial Electronics Industry Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Bureau officials attribute the industry's phenomenal growth to
efforts to create bigger companies in the past two years. The
Hunan Electronics Information Industry Group, which was founded in
1996, for example, had an output value of 1.74 billion yuan in
1997, accounting for 51 percent of the provincial total.
</P>
<P>
The company also has a 20.5 percent stake in the Hunan Computer
Joint Stock Co., Ltd., which was set up in July of last year and
went public with an issue of 45 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The province has set a target of 4.5 billion yuan this year for
the information technology industry, according to bureau
officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
