<DOCNO> XIE19980521.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Habibie, Indonesia's New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jakarta, May 21 (Xinhua) -- B.J. Habibie became Indonesian new
president Thursday morning. Following is a profile of the new
president.
</P>
<P>
Born in the remote village of Nepo, Parepare, South Sulawesi,
on June 25, 1936, Habibie was brought up in a strictly religious
Muslim family.
</P>
<P>
He, the third of four children in his family, began reading
newspapers when he was a child. His lifelong religious devotion
continued in adulthood.
</P>
<P>
His father, Alwi Abdul Jalil Habibie, from the South Sulawesi
town of Gorontalo, died when Habibie was 13 years old. Then his
Javanese mother brought her children to Bandung, West Java.
</P>
<P>
After attending the Bandung Institute of Technology for about a
year in 1954, Habibie won a scholarship from the Ministry of
Education and Culture to study aircraft construction engineering
in Aachen, Germany, a course he completed in 1960.
</P>
<P>
As a research assistant at Aachen's Technische Hocheschule
(1960-65), Habibie created a design of a deep sea submarine and a
high pressured and temperature room for Julich Atomic Center.
</P>
<P>
With the Hamburger Flugzeugbau (HF) aircraft industry, he
designed the world's first aircraft with one consolidated wing,
which remains the only aircraft in the world capable of vertical
landing and takeoff.
</P>
<P>
In 1974, President Soeharto summoned Habibie home and made him
his technological consultant. Habibie has been state minister of
research and technology since 1978.
</P>
<P>
His close ties with out-going president Soeharto began when he
was a teenager.
</P>
<P>
Habibie's strengths, according to political observer Riswandha,
include his popularity among the majority Muslim community, the
esteem he holds among youth and his long service as Soeharto's
minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
