<HEADLINE> Russia's Duma Seeks Bureaucracy Cuts To Pay Miners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma (the lower
house of parliament) Wednesday unanimously approved an amendment
to cut bureaucratic costs in order to raise miners' wages, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The bill, handled by Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko, amends
the 1998 budget, cutting 25 percent from the administrative
expenses (about 87.7 million U.S. dollars) to pay off wage debts
to coal miners.
</P>
<P>
The bill has also to be submitted to the Federation Council
(the upper house).
</P>
<P>
Reports said current strikes and protests in Russia have
blocked two branches of the Trans-Siberian Railway, closing coal
mines and bringing hundreds of trains to a stop.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Ministers Boris Yefimovich Nemtsov and Oleg
Nikolayevich Sysuyev have separately cancelled their Italian and
South Korean visits, and are preparing to go to the mineral areas
to deal with miners' strikes. 
</P>
