<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Fuzhou, capital of east China's Fujian Province, has taken
15 measures and formulated 29 preferential policies to help
laid-off workers from state-owned enterprise find jobs. Since last
year, 32,000 laid-off workers have found jobs, accounting for 87.6
percent of the total number of local laid-offs.
</P>
<P>
-- Follow years of development, the Yellow River Delta, one of
the three major river deltas in China, is ready for another round
of development and is expecting an economic boom in the 21st
century, experts predicted.
</P>
<P>
The delta boasts vast land mass and is rich in mineral
resources such as copper, gold and granite as well as water
resources.
</P>
<P>
-- Guangdong Province, an economic power house in southern
China, witnessed rapid increase in foreign trade in the first
quarter of this year, with imports reaching 17.6 billion US
dollars, and introduced overseas funds amounting to 3.06 billion
US dollars, representing increases of over 20 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- A frontpage article on how the people of
Zhuanglang County, northwest China's Gansu Province, turned barren
hills on the Loess Plateau into terraced and high-yield
farmland.
</P>
<P>
The county has built 940,000 mu (over 62,000 hectares) of
terraced land in the past 34 years and lifted over 70 percent of
the local poverty-stricken families out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
-- North China's Hebei Province is expecting a good wheat
harvest this year, with the total output projected to grow by 5
percent over last year's wheat output of 13.4 billion kilograms.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China has to beef up exports and foreign investment so as to
sustain a GDP growth rate of 8 percent for 1998, State Councillor
Wu Yi said after the April slowdown in the momentum of export
growth.
</P>
<P>
Customs figures show exports grew 7.9 percent last moth, down
form 9.2 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
-- China will launch a nationwide campaign to protect marine
environment and explore marine resource early next month. The
campaign, to begin June 6, aims to weed out malpractice in marine
exploration and to improve the supervision of environmental
protection. It is an effort in support the International Year of
the Ocean. 
</P>
