<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Female Journalists Embracing Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Women journalists in China view
computers as a way to raise their work efficiency and sharpen
their competitive edge -- much more than their male counterparts,
said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
However, male journalists are more interested in computers and
the Internet than female journalists, although there is no gender
difference in the frequency of computer use.
</P>
<P>
These are some of the findings of a survey conducted by the
Research Institute of Journalism under the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,100 journalists with the Xinhua News Agency, People's
Daily and China Daily were polled. Of them, 91.5 percent said
computers were available to them at work, but only 27 percent used
them every day, mainly for writing articles and searching for
information.
</P>
<P>
Those polled show little interest in using the Internet, with
only four percent browsing on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, the Internet cannot change the
principle that journalists must judge the value of news, but it
could serve as a tool for obtaining information.
</P>
<P>
Female and male journalists start on an equal footing in using
computers and the Internet. But they are constrained by factors
such as technical problems and lack of training, money and time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
