<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, May 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A vital communications satellite lost track of
Earth Tuesday night, disrupting services to nearly all of the
millions of pagers used nationwide in the United States and
blacking out some television and radio stations' programs.
</P>
<P>
Official of the Galaxy 4 satellite, PanAmSat, said they
expected the satellite to remain inoperable at least through
Wednesday and they started transferring services to other
satellites Wednesday and decided to move another satellite into
position in orbit. (US-Satellite-Outage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- The South African Defense Ministry is planning
to borrow money from private arms manufacturers to meet its arms
renewal demand, the ministry told parliament Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is because this year's budget allocation to the fund used
by the National Defense Force to buy and maintain major weaponry
falls far short of meeting contracts the defense force has already
signed, the ministry was quoted by South African Press Association
as saying. (S. Africa-Arms Purchase)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair on Wednesday
visited Belfast again for a last-ditch efforts to secure a yes
vote in the referendum on the Northern Ireland peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Joined by Conservative leader William Hague, Blair said he had
spent more time working on the Northern Ireland issue than any
other in his first year as prime minister and made an impassioned
plea to wavering Protestant voters to endorse the historic peace
deal in Friday's referendum. (UK-Blair-Referendum)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The German government has ordered the suspension of all
nuclear waste shipments to foreign reprocessing plants after
extremely high radioactive contaminations have been detected
outside many nuclear waste containers.
</P>
<P>
Because of the still undetermined contamination, the nuclear
waste transport to the British reprocessing plant at Sellafield
was also suspended Wednesday after a similar move on May 14
concerning the waste transport to the French La Hague plant, the
German Environment Ministry announced Wednesday. (Germany-Nuclear
Waste)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- U.N. arms inspectors continued their monitoring and
inspection activities in Iraq on Wednesday, with full cooperation
from the Iraqi side, the Iraqi News Agency INA reported.
</P>
<P>
Eleven monitoring groups of the U.N. Special Commission on
disarmament in Iraq, known as the UNSCOM, made surprise and
scheduled visits to 15 sites off monitoring, INA quoted an
official source at the Iraqi National Monitoring Department as
saying. (Iraq-UNSCOM-Inspection)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian Home Minister L. K. Advani on Wednesday
threatened to quell what he called Pakistan's proxy war in
India-held Kashmir and take pro-active manner against Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
In a strongly worded statement here, Advani alleged: "Up to
now, India's policy toward Pakistan's provocations has been
essentially reactive." (India-Pakistan-Threat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin called on the new
Russian government Wednesday to work as a single team, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony to introduce new government members in
the Kremlin, Yeltsin said the new government of Russia is not a
coalition and should work as a single
team. (Russia-Yeltsin-Government)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee claimed
Wednesday that India was "forced to conduct nuclear tests" to show
its strength.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks during his visit to the site where India
conducted five nuclear tests in 48 hours last
week. (India-Vajpayee-Nuclear Tests) 
