<HEADLINE> Finland, Spain Call for Cooperation in Northern Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Spain is backing Finland's
proposal for the European Union (EU) to promote cooperation in
northern Europe, Spanish Foreign Minister Abel Matutes said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Matutes, on a two-day visit to Helsinki, said the proposal
would enable the EU to fortify ties with non-EU member nations.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was put forward by Finnish Prime Minister Paavo
Lipponen in the autumn of 1997, asking the EU to enhance
cooperation with northern Europe, the Baltic states and the
northwestern part of Russia.
</P>
<P>
Matutes, who arrived on Tuesday, held talks with his Finnish
counterpart Tarja Halonen. The two discussed a wide range of
international issues, including the expansion of EU and NATO, the
EU single currency and relations between EU and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Finland and Spain, both members of the EU, have strengthened
high-level political consultations in a common effort to urge the
EU to forge closer links with Mediterranean and north European
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
