<BODY>
<HEADLINE> '98 Duty-Free Symposium Opens in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The '98 Duty-Free Symposium
opened here yesterday, with the participation of specialists,
and makers and suppliers of duty-free commodities from a dozen
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day symposium, the participants will discuss
the latest information and development trends of duty-free business
and ways to overcome the difficulties duty-free trade now faces.
</P>
<P>
A related exhibition will be held today.
</P>
<P>
Business people from about 40 countries and regions will
display various kinds of duty-free commodities during the show.
</P>
<P>
Duty free business worldwide has been suffering from the
adverse effect of the Asian financial crisis, and faces a
number of other problems, including how to use modern scientific
and technological methods to meet customers' demands and how to
achieve economies of scale to cater to the ever-growing market
competition, said Gai Zhixin, general manager of the China
Duty-Free Commodity Company.
</P>
<P>
Gai said that he hoped that the participants would help find
out ways to solve these problems.
</P>
<P>
The China Duty-Free Commodity Company, an affiliate of the China
National Tourism Administration, founded in 1984, is authorized to
exercise unified management of duty-free trade in China.
</P>
<P>
China now has 130 duty-free shops, which are distributed in 80
open ports of entry. Their annual sales amount to 200 million US
dollars. The China Duty-Free Commodity Company is in 20th place
among the world's top 50 companies handling duty-free commodities.
</P>
<P>
The annual duty-free symposium was first held in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
