<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Exports Down in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- After climbing 3.3 percent in
February, Canada's total exports fell 2.1 percent in March,
Statistics Canada said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Energy and agricultural products were among the biggest export
losers in March, bringing down Canada's total exports to 25.9
billion Canadian dollars (17.9 billion u.s. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Exports of energy products dropped 18.9 percent in March,
mainly because of the lower natural gas prices. Crude oil prices
also dropped owing to a mild February in the United States.
</P>
<P>
After rising sharply in the previous month, exports of
agricultural and fishing products tumbled 8.3 percent in March.
Lower exports of wheat to Asia and of malt and canola to South
America and Mexico are partly to blame, the statistics agency
said.
</P>
<P>
Canada's exports of forestry products edged down 2.6 percent in
the month. Lower newsprint exports were the main contributor to
the decline.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the slowdown in imports carried over into
March, chiefly because of continuing lower imports of machinery
and equipment and energy products.
</P>
<P>
In March, Canada's total imports were 24.3 billion dollars,
which was 1.2 percent down from the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The country's trade balance was 1.6 billion dollars in March,
down 300 million dollars from February, the agency added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
