<HEADLINE> Tutu Awarded Cape Town's City Honor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Truth and Reconciliation
Commission (TRC) Chairman Desmond Tutu on Wednesday received the
Freedom of Cape Town award, the city's highest honor, for his
contribution to South Africa's anti-apartheid movement.
</P>
<P>
The honor was bestowed on Tutu at a special meeting of the
Cape Town municipality in the civic center by Mayor Theresa
Solomon.
</P>
<P>
"We are gathered here to pay tribute to a man who has been at
the center of the struggle," Solomon was quoted by South African
Press Association as saying at the function, which was attended
by senior national, provincial and municipal officials.
</P>
<P>
She said that Tutu, as TRC chairman, also played a positive
role in the statutory body charged with finding out truth about
the past and recommending compensation for apartheid victims.
</P>
<P>
"Your legacy will live for generations," Solomon said, noting
that Cape Town was proud to bestow its highest honor on him.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was preceded by a peace march across the city in
remembrance of the historic march to parliament in 1989 led by
Tutu.
</P>
<P>
About 30,000 people took part in the march to protest against
the apartheid election at that time, which triggered nationwide
protests and brought down the apartheid rule.
</P>
<P>
Tutu was the seventh "freeman" in the city since the honor was
first granted in 1858. South African President Nelson Mandela was
awarded the honor0in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
