<HEADLINE> Blair Makes Last Push for Yes Vote in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair on
Wednesday visited Belfast again for a last-ditch efforts to secure
a yes vote in the referendum on the Northern Ireland peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Joined by Conservative leader William Hague, Blair said he had
spent more time working on the Northern Ireland issue than any
other in his first year as prime minister and made an impassioned
plea to wavering Protestant voters to endorse the historic peace
deal in Friday's referendum.
</P>
<P>
"I believe this agreement, fashioned as it has been on secure
principle, offers the best chance for people here...for peace and
hope and stability in the future," he told an audience of
academics at the University of Ulster in the northwestern town of
Coleraine.
</P>
<P>
The peace deal, reached on April 10 by the province's political
parties, preserves Northern Ireland's links with Britain but
builds closer ties with mainly Roman Catholic Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"This is the chance for Northern Ireland to gain a better
future. I don't know whether that chance will come again this
generation if we turn our back on it now," he was quoted by
Reuters as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that on Friday people, whatever their doubts...have
courage to vote for the future and for the prosperity and
stability we can bring."
</P>
<P>
During his trip to Belfast, his third visit this month, Blair
promised that anyone who used violence will be excluded from a
role in government and that prisoners will be kept in jail until
violence is given up for good.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that Northern Ireland might wait a long time
before it gets a better opportunity to resolve its troubled
history of political strife.
</P>
<P>
With the 40 per cent Catholic Irish nationalist minority firmly
behind the pact, polls forecast an overall cross-community
majority for the deal in Friday's referendum.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll on Wednesday showed that majorities of voters
in both the Irish Republic and Northern Ireland intend to back the
peace plan in the referendum.  
</P>
</TEXT>
