<HEADLINE> Dow Surges Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Blue-chip stocks on Wall Street
surged back toward record levels today, but the broad market were
less active in an uncertain direction of interest rates and
company profits.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average jumped 116.83 to 9,171.48,
about 40 points from last Wednesday's record of 9,211.84, despite
a brief dip into negative territory during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market indicators were mixed. The technology-heavy Nasdaq
composite index suffered the heaviest damage after Dell Computer
reported a healthy quarterly profit that failed to meet Wall
Street's more enthusiastic forecasts.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 8.25 to 1,117.77, about 13
points from the record of 1,130.54, set nearly a month ago on
April 23. The Nasdaq composite fell 14.11 to 1,831.76.
</P>
<P>
Advancers barely outnumbered decliners on the New York Stock
Exchange. However, in Nasdaq trading, decliners outnumbered
advancers by a 4-to-3 margin.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume totaled 586.33 million shares as against Tuesday's
lower-than-average tally of 565.37 million.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 4.71 to 578.63, about 7 points
from its record high, while the American Stock Exchange composite
index fell 0.47 to 732.22.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.24 to
468.61.  
</P>
</TEXT>
