<HEADLINE> Former Junta Members Back to Apologize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Several members of Sierra Leone's
ousted military junta Wednesday apologized to the people of the
country for what the junta has done and is doing.
</P>
<P>
According to a British Broadcasting Corporation report
monitored here, these junta members include the former
secretary-general, mayor of the capital Freetown and transport
secretary, as well as two civilians.
</P>
<P>
They came back last week from neighboring Guinea where they
fled over the fall of the junta in mid-February and are now being
held in the custody of the west African peacekeeping force
ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The former secretary-general of the dislodged junta said they
wanted and needed to come and to see how they can help stop the
evil of the junta remnants against the ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
Under the intensified mopping up exercise launched by ECOMOG
and allies, the remnants of the junta forces and allied rebels
are reportedly perpetrating atrocities in the east and north of
the country, killing and maiming by chopping off people's hands
and legs.
</P>
<P>
The former junta secretary-general condemned the mutilation of
the people and called on the fleeing junta forces to lay down
their guns and surrender.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the junta leader Johnny Paul Koroma to stop
what is happening or give instructions to stop what is happening.
</P>
<P>
But none of them said they were in contact with any junta
members and asked for a press conference to convey their message.
</P>
<P>
Despite their apologies, Sierra Leoneans are still
unforgiving, particularly when everyday people come from villages
across the east and north with amputated hands and legs.
</P>
<P>
The people of the country will not change their mind at the
apologies, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Like most of their former colleagues, according to the report,
these former junta members are going to be tried. The former
militiamen will go to the court martial with the two civilians to
the civil court.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leonean government has earlier tried two groups of
more than 30 former junta members and collaborators with the
charge of treason.  
</P>
</TEXT>
