<HEADLINE> S. African Navy Facing Collapse for Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 20 (Xinhua) -- South African navy and the
military medical services might both be heading for total
collapse as the cash-strapped defense ministry can not afford to
buy new equipment, the ministry warned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The army was also unable to perform its primary duty of
protecting the country's borders, the ministry said in its
1998/99 budget document presented to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
As growing personnel costs are squeezing out funds for
operating costs and new equipment, readiness and service levels
would reach an "unprecedented low", South African Press
Association quoted the ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the navy, the shortage of cash for spares meant ships and
submarines were being cannibalized and would have to be phased
out sooner than planned.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that by 2002 the navy would no longer be able
to run any submarines, and its surface ships would cease to
operate by 2005.
</P>
<P>
"There is a distinct probability that the navy will enter a
period of irreversible decline until it...collapses," the
document said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it said although the budget for the defense force's
medical services was being raised by 16.2 percent, this would be
affected by the 21 percent medical inflation rate and growing
demand on medical services.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the services would no longer be able to fulfill its
mandate of providing "operationally essential" medical services
to South African National Defense Force members and their
dependants.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said personnel are insufficiently trained for
their duties, productivity and morale are declining, and
urgently-needed people with the right qualifications are leaving.
</P>
</TEXT>
