<HEADLINE> UK to Take Action against Football Hooligans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- British Home Secretary Jack Straw
took measures Wednesday to prevent his country's football fans
from stirring up trouble in France during next month's World Cup,
media reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Straw asked parliament to give British courts the right to
prosecute any football fans convicted of violence in France and
prevent them from travelling to other soccer matches abroad.
</P>
<P>
He told parliament that "We have been able to reach a bilateral
agreement with the French authorities in advance of the World
Cup".
</P>
<P>
"This will allow us to take action in our courts in addition to
prosecution and conviction in France," he said.
</P>
<P>
Straw added that while French magistrates will be available at
each of the World Cup venues to deal swiftly with any violence,
Britain, in turn, will ask its courts to issue a restriction order
when those hooligans return to the UK. This will prevent their
attendance at future matches abroad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
