<HEADLINE> S. African Defense Seeking Private Fund for Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The South African Defense
Ministry is planning to borrow money from private arms
manufacturers to meet its arms renewal demand, the ministry told
parliament Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is because this year's budget allocation to the fund used
by the National Defense Force to buy and maintain major weaponry
falls far short of meeting contracts the defense force has
already signed, the ministry was quoted by South African Press
Association as saying.
</P>
<P>
The current budget earmarked 688 million Rand (136 million
U.S. Dollars) for the weaponry fund, which is down 38.1 percent
in real terms on the 1997/98 budget and could only cover half of
the contract commitments, ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
This amount is just enough to buy a third of a tank regiment,
or 13 tanks, 1.3 advanced fighter aircraft or two-thirds of a
corvette, a defense force weapon acquisition official said.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministry had asked state expenditure to approve
bridging finance of 771 million Rand (152 million U.S. Dollars)
from the armaments industry. The fund would be repaid from the
defense budget over four years.
</P>
<P>
The financing is expected to be organized by Armscor, the
state arms procurement agency, from the industry locally or
overseas, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry proposes that manufacturers simply grant the
ministry credit for the material they delivered, and the eventual
repayment would include interest charges.
</P>
<P>
The request is being considered by Finance Minister Trevor
Manuel, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
