<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell to profit
taking Wednesday as turmoil in Indonesia continued and the U.S.
record trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's fall came one day after it hit its highest level
against the yen since August 1991.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 135.98 yen,
down from 136.44 late Tuesday. The dollar also was also traded at
1.7698 marks, down from 1.7834.
</P>
<P>
Traders sold off the U.S. currency in the face of a Commerce
Department report showing that the U.S. trade deficit soared to a
record 13 billion U.S. dollars in March, the largest imbalance
since the government started tracking merchandise and services
trade on a monthly basis in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday:
1.4758 Swiss francs, down from 1.4801; 5.9340 French francs, down
from 5.9800; 1,744.00 Italian lire, down from 1,758.75; and 1.4493
Canadian dollars, up from 1.4492.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6324 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6213 U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
