<HEADLINE> Annan Reports on Identification Process in Western Sahara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- While the pace of
identification in Western Sahara was slow during the month of
April, 1998, the parties concerned had demonstrated their
willingness to cooperate and to increase the pace substantially,
U.N. secretary-General Kofi Annan said in his latest report on
Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
In the report, Annan said the process of identification in
Western Sahara could be completed at the latest by the end of
August 1998, provided the POLISARIO Front and Morocco cooperate
fully.
</P>
<P>
However, Annan said, no consensus solution on ways of dealing
with the 65,000 applicants from the contested tribes has been
found as yet.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said his Special Representative will continue to
discuss with the Government of Morocco and the POLISARIO Front
practical and concrete ways of resolving this problem by the end
of June 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General urged the parties to cooperate with his
Special Representative in the search for appropriate solutions,
with a view to enabling the successful and timely completion of
the identification process.  
</P>
</TEXT>
