<HEADLINE> U.S. Unveils New 20 Dollar Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. monetary authorities
today unveiled the redesigned 20 dollar note, which includes new
and modified security features to deter counterfeiting of U.S.
currency.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Federal Reserve banks and the Secret Service
introduced the money in Washington, New York, San Francisco, Los
Angeles and Huston to the press, hoping to spread the public
education of the new features of the U.S. currency quickly.
</P>
<P>
"Counterfeit money making has been at a surprisingly low level
since the U.S. government introduced the redesigned series
starting from 1996," said Joseph Botta, vice president of the
Federal Reserve Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
He noted that about a total of 230 million U.S. dollars worth
of counterfeit dollars were discovered last year, and only 14
million dollars worth were in new 100 and 50 dollars. Most of the
fake money were found before they entered the market, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Series 1996 20-dollar note will be introduced in the fall
of 1998. The new 50-dollar note was introduced in October 1997,
and the 100-dollar note was issued in March 1996. Lower
denominations will follow.
</P>
<P>
There will be no recall or devaluation of U.S. currency already
in circulation.
</P>
<P>
"We are most gratified with the successful introduction of the
new notes," said the Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. To
date, about two thirds of all 100-dollar bills and about a third
of all 50-dollar bills are the new series 1996 notes, he said.
</P>
<P>
About 88 billion U.S. dollar worth of 20-dollar notes is
currently in circulation, 80 percent of those are in the U.S. More
than 450 billion worth of U.S. currency circulates around the
globe, according to Fed statistics.
</P>
<P>
The 20-dollar notes will be in bigger circulation, because they
are supplied by most of the ATM machines across the country.
</P>
<P>
The overall architecture of the 20-dollar note has carried more
new and modified security features. Microprinting and security
threads, which first appeared in the 1991 series currency,
continue to prove effective deterrents and appear in the new note
series. For example, the security thread is in green and on the
left side of the Fed seal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
